1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,033
- My strength lies not in my name,

2
00:00:04,266 --> 00:00:07,133
but in the backing of 1.4 billion Indians,

3
00:00:07,600 --> 00:00:10,600
and thousands of years of timeless culture
and heritage.

4
00:00:11,800 --> 00:00:16,166
So, wherever I go, I carry with me the
essence of

5
00:00:16,266 --> 00:00:22,033
thousands of years of Vedic tradition, the
timeless teachings of Swami Vivekananda,

6
00:00:22,766 --> 00:00:28,700
and the blessings, dreams, and aspirations
of 1.4 billion Indians.

7
00:00:30,166 --> 00:00:35,600
When I shake hands with a world leader,
it's not Modi,

8
00:00:35,700 --> 00:00:38,500
but 1.4 billion Indians
doing so.

9
00:00:39,400 --> 00:00:43,633
So, this isn't my strength at all. It is
rather the strength of India.

10
00:00:44,433 --> 00:00:49,800
Whenever we speak of peace, the world
listens to us.

11
00:00:50,866 --> 00:00:56,833
Because India is the land of Gautama
Buddha and Mahatma Gandhi.

12
00:00:57,433 --> 00:01:02,033
And Indians aren't hardwired to espouse
strife and conflict.

13
00:01:03,400 --> 00:01:05,600
We espouse harmony instead.

14
00:01:06,200 --> 00:01:09,400
We seek neither to wage war against
nature,

15
00:01:09,433 --> 00:01:12,000
nor to foster strife among
nations.

16
00:01:12,400 --> 00:01:14,400
We stand for peace.

17
00:01:14,633 --> 00:01:20,433
And wherever we can act as peacemakers, we
have gladly embraced that responsibility.

18
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:24,533
My early life was
spent in extreme poverty.

19
00:01:25,333 --> 00:01:32,000
But we never really felt the burden of
poverty.

20
00:01:33,100 --> 00:01:37,400
You see, someone who is used to wearing
fine shoes

21
00:01:38,233 --> 00:01:42,300
will feel their absence when they don’t
have them.

22
00:01:42,700 --> 00:01:46,166
But for us, we had never worn shoes in our
lives,

23
00:01:46,433 --> 00:01:50,500
so how would we even know that wearing
shoes was a big deal?

24
00:01:51,100 --> 00:01:54,033
We weren’t in a position to compare.

25
00:01:54,200 --> 00:01:55,833
That’s just how we lived.

26
00:01:56,100 --> 00:02:03,500
When I became Prime Minister, I specially
invited Pakistan to my swearing-in ceremony

27
00:02:03,933 --> 00:02:05,900
so we could turn over a new leaf.

28
00:02:06,833 --> 00:02:12,066
Yet, every noble attempt at fostering
peace was met with hostility and betrayal.

29
00:02:13,066 --> 00:02:17,066
We sincerely hope that wisdom prevails
upon them

30
00:02:17,833 --> 00:02:19,900
and they choose the path of peace.

31
00:02:20,400 --> 00:02:23,766
I believe even the people of Pakistan long
for peace.

32
00:02:24,333 --> 00:02:28,566
Look, regarding what you said about
criticism and how I deal with it,

33
00:02:29,500 --> 00:02:33,700
if I had to summarize in one sentence, I
welcome it.

34
00:02:35,400 --> 00:02:37,333
I have a strong belief

35
00:02:38,900 --> 00:02:43,900
that criticism is
the soul of democracy.

36
00:02:44,466 --> 00:02:48,100
I want to tell all young people the
following:

37
00:02:49,600 --> 00:02:56,600
No matter how dark the night may seem,

38
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:04,600
it is still just night, and morning is
bound to come.

39
00:03:07,766 --> 00:03:11,600
- The following is a
conversation with Narendra Modi,

40
00:03:11,700 --> 00:03:14,366
the Prime Minister of India.

41
00:03:15,133 --> 00:03:20,766
It was one of the most moving
conversations and experiences of my life.

42
00:03:20,900 --> 00:03:24,500
Allow me here to say a few words about it.

43
00:03:24,500 --> 00:03:27,733
Please skip ahead straight to
our conversation, if you like.

44
00:03:28,600 --> 00:03:32,200
Narendra Modi's life story is incredible.

45
00:03:32,300 --> 00:03:37,300
He rose from poverty to lead a
nation of 1.4 billion people,

46
00:03:37,300 --> 00:03:39,466
the biggest democracy in the world,

47
00:03:39,466 --> 00:03:45,066
where he won epic-scale elections
for Prime Minister three times.

48
00:03:45,066 --> 00:03:49,166
As a leader, he fought for
ideas that unite his nation of India,

49
00:03:49,200 --> 00:03:51,566
a nation that is composed
of a large number

50
00:03:51,566 --> 00:03:54,833
of highly varied and
disparate cultures and peoples

51
00:03:54,833 --> 00:04:00,800
who have a long history marked by
religious, social, and political frictions.

52
00:04:01,233 --> 00:04:05,666
He's known for taking decisive,
at times, controversial actions

53
00:04:05,666 --> 00:04:12,166
for which he's loved by hundreds of millions
of people, and is also criticized by many.

54
00:04:12,166 --> 00:04:16,566
We discuss all of this at
length in this conversation.

55
00:04:16,566 --> 00:04:20,866
On the world stage,
he's respected as a peacemaker and friend

56
00:04:20,866 --> 00:04:26,633
by most major world leaders, even those
whose nations are at war with each other,

57
00:04:26,633 --> 00:04:30,600
from United States to China,
to Ukraine and Russia,

58
00:04:30,600 --> 00:04:35,000
to Israel, Palestine, and the Middle East,
and everywhere else.

59
00:04:35,866 --> 00:04:40,800
Now, at this moment in history,
it's clear, at least to me,

60
00:04:40,800 --> 00:04:44,300
that the flourishing of human civilization
hangs in the balance,

61
00:04:44,300 --> 00:04:48,900
with several wars on the brink of escalation
to regional and even global conflict,

62
00:04:48,900 --> 00:04:51,666
rising tensions between nuclear powers,

63
00:04:51,666 --> 00:04:54,700
technological developments
from AI to nuclear fusion

64
00:04:54,700 --> 00:05:00,233
that aim to completely transform
society and geopolitics as we know it,

65
00:05:00,233 --> 00:05:05,566
and, of course, generally,
increasing political and cultural turmoil.

66
00:05:05,566 --> 00:05:10,333
So now more than ever,
we need great leaders,

67
00:05:10,333 --> 00:05:14,500
great peacemakers, who build
bridges, not destroy them,

68
00:05:15,400 --> 00:05:17,466
who may preserve the
identity of their nations,

69
00:05:17,466 --> 00:05:22,600
but still celebrate the common
humanity of all of us, all people on Earth.

70
00:05:23,533 --> 00:05:28,300
For this and many other reasons,
this conversation with Prime Minister Modi

71
00:05:28,300 --> 00:05:31,766
was one of the most
remarkable I've ever had.

72
00:05:32,666 --> 00:05:38,933
You may hear such words and think
that I'm just enamored by power or access.

73
00:05:38,933 --> 00:05:43,333
No, never was, never will be.

74
00:05:43,333 --> 00:05:48,266
I do not idolize anyone,
especially those in power.

75
00:05:48,266 --> 00:05:50,533
I'm generally skeptical
of power, money, and fame

76
00:05:50,533 --> 00:05:54,200
because of their natural
corrupting influence on the mind,

77
00:05:54,233 --> 00:05:56,466
the heart, the soul of a person.

78
00:05:57,333 --> 00:05:59,700
The whole point of all the conversations

79
00:05:59,700 --> 00:06:03,400
I've had in my life, on mic and off mic,

80
00:06:03,400 --> 00:06:06,100
is that I try to see and
explore the full complexity

81
00:06:06,100 --> 00:06:09,600
of every human being,
the good and the bad.

82
00:06:10,800 --> 00:06:15,133
I believe we're all the same
in a deep fundamental sense.

83
00:06:15,133 --> 00:06:18,866
All capable of good, all capable of evil,

84
00:06:18,866 --> 00:06:22,233
all carry stories of
pain and stories of hope,

85
00:06:23,400 --> 00:06:27,300
whether you're a world
leader or a truck driver,

86
00:06:27,300 --> 00:06:32,966
a coal miner or a farmer
in the American Midwest, and, by the way,

87
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:38,366
I will be talking to a lot of the
latter kind of folk this year, off mic,

88
00:06:38,366 --> 00:06:41,900
and maybe even on mic, as I
travel the US and the world.

89
00:06:42,766 --> 00:06:45,366
My brief statements
here about Narendra Modi

90
00:06:45,366 --> 00:06:51,166
are about both him as a leader
and especially him as a human being.

91
00:06:51,166 --> 00:06:53,400
In the extensive time I spent with him,

92
00:06:53,400 --> 00:06:56,633
I spoke with him off mic and on mic.

93
00:06:56,633 --> 00:06:59,100
It was a deeply personal human interaction

94
00:06:59,100 --> 00:07:04,466
characterized by warmth, kindness, humor,
inner and outer peace,

95
00:07:04,466 --> 00:07:08,566
and absolute focus on the
conversation between us

96
00:07:08,566 --> 00:07:12,066
in the present moment as
if nothing else existed.

97
00:07:12,866 --> 00:07:14,700
I have heard from many people

98
00:07:14,700 --> 00:07:17,900
that he treats everyone he
meets in this empathic way,

99
00:07:18,666 --> 00:07:20,666
no matter where they come from,

100
00:07:20,666 --> 00:07:22,666
or what their position is in this world.

101
00:07:23,933 --> 00:07:26,100
So, for those and many other reasons,

102
00:07:26,100 --> 00:07:30,200
this really was an incredible experience
I will never forget.

103
00:07:31,333 --> 00:07:33,700
Oh, and by the way,

104
00:07:33,700 --> 00:07:35,733
we made captions and
voiceover audio tracks

105
00:07:35,733 --> 00:07:39,566
available in English,
Hindi, and other languages.

106
00:07:39,566 --> 00:07:44,366
You can also listen to the original
mixed-language version where I speak English

107
00:07:44,366 --> 00:07:47,300
and Prime Minister Modi speaks Hindi.

108
00:07:47,300 --> 00:07:51,933
Separately, you can choose to turn
on subtitles in your preferred language.

109
00:07:52,766 --> 00:07:55,966
On YouTube, you can switch
between language audio tracks

110
00:07:56,000 --> 00:08:00,333
by clicking the Settings gear icon,
then clicking Audio Track,

111
00:08:00,333 --> 00:08:03,466
and then selecting the
language you prefer.

112
00:08:03,466 --> 00:08:06,500
For fully English overdub, select English,

113
00:08:06,500 --> 00:08:10,166
for fully Hindi overdub, select Hindi,

114
00:08:10,166 --> 00:08:12,266
and to listen to the original
mixed-language version,

115
00:08:12,266 --> 00:08:15,633
where I speak English and Prime
Minister Modi Speaks Hindi,

116
00:08:15,633 --> 00:08:20,066
please select Hindi Latin audio track.

117
00:08:20,066 --> 00:08:23,733
So you can listen either to a version
that is all one language,

118
00:08:23,733 --> 00:08:27,766
or to the original mixed-language version
with subtitles in your preferred language,

119
00:08:27,766 --> 00:08:30,266
the default is English overdub.

120
00:08:30,266 --> 00:08:34,466
All thanks to ElevenLabs and
a great team of translators,

121
00:08:34,466 --> 00:08:37,900
we do our best to bring the
Prime Minister's voice to life

122
00:08:37,900 --> 00:08:41,666
with AI voice cloning in English.

123
00:08:41,666 --> 00:08:45,466
I promise that we will
continue to work very hard

124
00:08:45,466 --> 00:08:48,500
to break down the barriers
that language creates,

125
00:08:48,500 --> 00:08:50,466
and try to make these conversations

126
00:08:50,466 --> 00:08:54,000
as accessible as possible
to everyone in the world.

127
00:08:55,166 --> 00:09:00,333
Anyway, let me pause one more
time to say a big thank you.

128
00:09:00,666 --> 00:09:03,633
What a wild ride this life has been.

129
00:09:03,733 --> 00:09:08,166
It's an honor for me to be on
it with all of you. I love you all.

130
00:09:09,366 --> 00:09:12,133
This is the "Lex Fridman Podcast."

131
00:09:12,166 --> 00:09:17,000
And now, dear friends, here's
the Prime Minister of India,

132
00:09:17,033 --> 00:09:18,733
Narendra Modi.

133
00:09:19,733 --> 00:09:21,633
So, I should also say,
I’m fasting right now.

134
00:09:21,733 --> 00:09:24,433
It’s been almost two days, 45 hours.

135
00:09:24,833 --> 00:09:29,333
So just water, no food, in honor of this
conversation,

136
00:09:29,333 --> 00:09:33,133
just to get in the right mindset, get into
the spiritual level.

137
00:09:33,333 --> 00:09:35,933
I’ve read that you often
fast for many days.

138
00:09:36,333 --> 00:09:41,266
Can you explain why you fast and where
does your mind go when you fast?

139
00:09:42,333 --> 00:09:49,166
- First of all, I’m truly, pleasantly
surprised and honored that you’re fasting.

140
00:09:50,133 --> 00:09:56,833
All the more because it feels like you're
fasting as a tribute of respect for me.

141
00:09:57,966 --> 00:10:01,233
So I express my deepest gratitude to you
for doing this.

142
00:10:03,266 --> 00:10:04,833
In India,

143
00:10:08,433 --> 00:10:11,333
our religious traditions

144
00:10:13,166 --> 00:10:16,433
are actually a
way of life.

145
00:10:20,466 --> 00:10:26,900
Our Supreme Court once gave a brilliant
interpretation of Hinduism.

146
00:10:28,166 --> 00:10:35,133
They have stated that Hinduism is not
about rituals or methods of worship.

147
00:10:36,033 --> 00:10:41,066
But rather it is a way of living,

148
00:10:41,966 --> 00:10:44,233
a philosophy that guides life itself.

149
00:10:45,266 --> 00:10:47,333
And in our scriptures,

150
00:10:49,066 --> 00:10:52,500
there is deep discussion

151
00:10:53,300 --> 00:10:55,200
on elevating

152
00:10:56,633 --> 00:11:01,233
the body, mind, intellect,
soul, and humanity.

153
00:11:02,500 --> 00:11:08,266
They outline various paths, traditions,
and systems to achieve this

154
00:11:09,533 --> 00:11:12,133
and fasting is one of them.

155
00:11:13,033 --> 00:11:15,500
But fasting alone isn’t everything.

156
00:11:18,100 --> 00:11:23,300
In India, whether you see it culturally or
philosophically,

157
00:11:24,900 --> 00:11:28,466
sometimes, I see that fasting is a way to
cultivate discipline.

158
00:11:28,500 --> 00:11:30,933
If I put it in simple terms,

159
00:11:31,333 --> 00:11:36,300
or explain it to the viewers who are
unfamiliar with India,

160
00:11:37,266 --> 00:11:40,833
it is a powerful tool to bring both

161
00:11:40,866 --> 00:11:45,500
the inner and outer
self into balance.

162
00:11:47,033 --> 00:11:51,733
It shapes life in profound ways.
When you fast,

163
00:11:53,133 --> 00:11:57,533
You may have noticed, as you said, you've
been fasting on water for two days.

164
00:11:58,500 --> 00:12:02,266
Every single one of your senses,

165
00:12:03,633 --> 00:12:07,066
especially smell, touch, and taste,

166
00:12:08,266 --> 00:12:10,833
becomes highly sensitive.

167
00:12:11,066 --> 00:12:14,833
You may even notice the subtle aroma of
water itself,

168
00:12:15,533 --> 00:12:19,066
something you probably never noticed
before when drinking it.

169
00:12:19,233 --> 00:12:22,300
If someone walks past you carrying tea,

170
00:12:22,866 --> 00:12:25,833
you will catch its aroma, just like you
would with coffee.

171
00:12:26,733 --> 00:12:30,200
A small flower you’ve seen before, you
will see it again today,

172
00:12:30,933 --> 00:12:34,266
but now, you can perceive its details more
vividly.

173
00:12:35,233 --> 00:12:37,900
Your senses become extra sharp,

174
00:12:38,333 --> 00:12:43,633
highly aware, and
fully tuned in.

175
00:12:44,533 --> 00:12:48,833
And uh, their capability,

176
00:12:50,333 --> 00:12:56,433
to observe and to respond, multiplies and
grows sharper.

177
00:12:57,833 --> 00:13:00,066
I have personally often experienced this.

178
00:13:00,600 --> 00:13:04,033
Another thing I’ve experienced is that
fasting

179
00:13:05,333 --> 00:13:11,466
can greatly accelerate the thinking
process and can, uh,

180
00:13:12,200 --> 00:13:14,166
give a fresh
perspective.

181
00:13:14,533 --> 00:13:16,633
You start thinking outside the box.

182
00:13:17,333 --> 00:13:21,066
I don’t know if everyone experiences this,
but I certainly do.

183
00:13:22,033 --> 00:13:25,700
Most people assume that fasting

184
00:13:26,433 --> 00:13:30,633
simply
means giving up food or not eating.

185
00:13:32,733 --> 00:13:35,333
But that’s just the physical aspect of
fasting.

186
00:13:36,633 --> 00:13:40,700
If someone is forced to go without food
due to hardship,

187
00:13:40,933 --> 00:13:44,533
with an empty stomach,
can we call that fasting?

188
00:13:45,266 --> 00:13:47,866
Fasting is actually a scientific process.

189
00:13:48,066 --> 00:13:52,833
Whenever I fast for an extended period, I
prepare my body in advance.

190
00:13:53,633 --> 00:13:55,733
For 5 to 7 days before the fast,

191
00:13:56,133 --> 00:14:00,433
I follow various Ayurvedic practices and
yoga practices,

192
00:14:00,433 --> 00:14:05,966
along with other traditional cleansing
methods to internally reset my system.

193
00:14:07,566 --> 00:14:10,433
Before actually beginning the fast,

194
00:14:11,533 --> 00:14:15,733
I make sure to drink a lot of water, as
much as possible.

195
00:14:16,400 --> 00:14:19,166
So, you could say that this detoxification
process

196
00:14:19,666 --> 00:14:22,266
helps prepare my body in the best possible
way.

197
00:14:22,966 --> 00:14:27,133
And once I begin fasting, for me, it’s an
act of devotion.

198
00:14:27,933 --> 00:14:30,533
For me fasting is a form of
self-discipline.

199
00:14:31,266 --> 00:14:33,066
For me, personally,

200
00:14:34,833 --> 00:14:38,933
even while I go about
doing my daily activities during a fast,

201
00:14:40,066 --> 00:14:47,066
my mind remains deeply introspective and
focused inward.

202
00:14:48,133 --> 00:14:52,033
And that experience is profoundly
transformative for me.

203
00:14:54,133 --> 00:14:59,166
My practice of fasting didn’t come from
reading books, listening to sermons,

204
00:14:59,766 --> 00:15:04,633
or following a tradition just because my
family happened to have observed it.

205
00:15:05,866 --> 00:15:08,433
It came from my own personal experience.

206
00:15:10,133 --> 00:15:11,366
During my school days,

207
00:15:13,166 --> 00:15:17,633
there was a movement inspired by Mahatma
Gandhi’s vision

208
00:15:19,200 --> 00:15:21,566
his vision of cow protection.

209
00:15:21,666 --> 00:15:24,233
The government had not enacted any laws at
the time.

210
00:15:24,633 --> 00:15:26,666
At the time, people across the country

211
00:15:29,333 --> 00:15:34,533
observed a one-day fast by gathering in
public places in silent protest.

212
00:15:36,433 --> 00:15:41,133
We were just kids, probably had just
finished primary school.

213
00:15:42,933 --> 00:15:45,333
Something inside me said, "I should be
part of this."

214
00:15:46,433 --> 00:15:49,866
And that was the first time in my life I
experienced fasting.

215
00:15:50,966 --> 00:15:57,433
At such a young age, I felt neither hunger
nor any desire for food.

216
00:15:57,833 --> 00:16:02,666
Instead, I felt a new awareness, a surge
of energy within me.

217
00:16:04,033 --> 00:16:07,933
So, I became convinced that fasting is a
science,

218
00:16:08,666 --> 00:16:12,366
far beyond just skipping meals.

219
00:16:12,633 --> 00:16:14,866
It is something far greater than that.

220
00:16:15,433 --> 00:16:17,333
Then, gradually,

221
00:16:18,900 --> 00:16:23,966
I refined my body and
mind through various experiments.

222
00:16:25,033 --> 00:16:28,966
Over time, it became a long and
disciplined journey for me.

223
00:16:31,433 --> 00:16:34,533
And one thing is certain, fasting never
slows me down.

224
00:16:35,666 --> 00:16:40,933
I work just as much as usual, sometimes I
even work more.

225
00:16:41,666 --> 00:16:45,800
And another fascinating thing I’ve noticed
is that

226
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:48,666
when I need to express my
thoughts,

227
00:16:49,933 --> 00:16:53,866
I’m amazed at where they come from and how
they flow.

228
00:16:55,066 --> 00:16:55,433
- Yeah.

229
00:16:55,533 --> 00:16:57,666
- It’s truly an incredible experience.

230
00:16:58,133 --> 00:17:02,133
- So you still do meetings with
world leaders,

231
00:17:02,566 --> 00:17:05,233
you still manage the affairs of India,

232
00:17:05,833 --> 00:17:09,833
you still carry out your role as a leader
on the world stage,

233
00:17:09,966 --> 00:17:13,033
all fasted and sometimes nine days?

234
00:17:14,133 --> 00:17:16,800
- Well, this practice has a long
historical context.

235
00:17:17,000 --> 00:17:19,266
I hope it may be
interesting for those listening.

236
00:17:20,066 --> 00:17:23,266
There is an ancient tradition in India
called Chaturmas.

237
00:17:24,333 --> 00:17:29,233
During the monsoon season, we know that
the digestion tends to slow down.

238
00:17:30,033 --> 00:17:31,933
And so, in this season,

239
00:17:33,300 --> 00:17:36,500
many people in India follow the practice
of eating only a

240
00:17:36,533 --> 00:17:38,733
single meal within 24
hours.

241
00:17:38,933 --> 00:17:42,366
For me, this starts around mid-June

242
00:17:43,333 --> 00:17:45,600
and
goes on until after Diwali,

243
00:17:45,633 --> 00:17:47,100
around November.

244
00:17:48,333 --> 00:17:50,733
For about four to four and a half months,

245
00:17:51,633 --> 00:17:58,066
I follow this tradition of eating only
once in 24 hours.

246
00:17:59,033 --> 00:18:02,500
Then comes the Navratri festival in India,

247
00:18:02,700 --> 00:18:06,066
which usually falls in September or
October

248
00:18:07,466 --> 00:18:10,933
During this time, the whole country
celebrates Durga Puja,

249
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:13,733
a festival of strength, devotion, and
spiritual discipline.

250
00:18:14,566 --> 00:18:16,666
This lasts for nine days.

251
00:18:17,333 --> 00:18:21,833
During this time, I completely abstain
from food and only drink hot water.

252
00:18:21,933 --> 00:18:26,533
Although, drinking hot water has always
been a part of my daily routine.

253
00:18:27,133 --> 00:18:31,466
My past lifestyle was such that I
naturally developed this habit over time.

254
00:18:32,966 --> 00:18:35,766
Then, in March or April,

255
00:18:36,733 --> 00:18:41,466
another Navratri
occurs, called Chaitra Navratri.

256
00:18:42,066 --> 00:18:46,533
This year, it will likely begin around
March 31st.

257
00:18:47,933 --> 00:18:54,033
During this nine-day fast, I eat only one
specific fruit, once a day.

258
00:18:55,766 --> 00:18:59,233
So for those nine days, if let’s say I
choose papaya.

259
00:19:00,133 --> 00:19:03,533
then for all nine days, I won’t touch
anything else, just papaya.

260
00:19:04,966 --> 00:19:10,833
That too I eat only once a day. That’s how
I follow my nine-day fasting routine.

261
00:19:11,266 --> 00:19:14,766
So there are numerous fasts I keep
throughout the year,

262
00:19:14,966 --> 00:19:18,566
and this has become a
deeply ingrained tradition in my life.

263
00:19:20,500 --> 00:19:25,500
Perhaps I can say that I’ve been following
these practices for 50 to 55 years.

264
00:19:25,566 --> 00:19:30,566
- Has there been times when you met with a
world leader and completely fasted?

265
00:19:30,766 --> 00:19:32,633
And maybe what do they think about that?

266
00:19:32,666 --> 00:19:35,066
What do they think about your ability to
do that kind of thing?

267
00:19:35,466 --> 00:19:40,366
And you're right, I should mention that
from even my two days,

268
00:19:40,566 --> 00:19:42,333
my ability to be
present,

269
00:19:42,433 --> 00:19:48,966
my ability to sense everything sharply
focus on this experience is elevated.

270
00:19:49,233 --> 00:19:51,766
But yes, is there stories with a world
leader

271
00:19:52,033 --> 00:19:55,033
that maybe jumped to mind when you were
fasted?

272
00:19:55,533 --> 00:20:00,166
- Well, most of the time, I don’t even let
people know about it.

273
00:20:01,466 --> 00:20:06,133
It’s my personal matter. So I never publicized
it,

274
00:20:06,533 --> 00:20:08,833
but people gradually started finding out.

275
00:20:09,500 --> 00:20:13,433
It became known only after I became
Chief Minister and Prime Minister.

276
00:20:13,433 --> 00:20:17,133
Otherwise, it was purely personal.

277
00:20:18,233 --> 00:20:21,566
But now that it’s out in the open, I don’t
mind sharing.

278
00:20:21,633 --> 00:20:24,700
If someone asks, I tell them so it might
be useful to them.

279
00:20:24,866 --> 00:20:26,866
Because it’s not my personal property.

280
00:20:26,900 --> 00:20:30,233
It’s my experience. And if that can help
someone, why not share it?

281
00:20:30,433 --> 00:20:34,333
After all, my life has always been devoted
to the well-being of others.

282
00:20:34,400 --> 00:20:37,066
For example, after I
became Prime Minister,

283
00:20:37,433 --> 00:20:43,633
I had a bilateral meeting at the White
House with President Obama,

284
00:20:44,033 --> 00:20:46,333
and he had also arranged a formal dinner.

285
00:20:47,433 --> 00:20:50,533
Then, as discussions between the two
governments progressed,

286
00:20:50,966 --> 00:20:54,066
someone said, "Please, join us for
dinner."

287
00:20:54,100 --> 00:20:56,866
To which another replied, "But the Prime
Minister doesn’t eat."

288
00:20:57,866 --> 00:21:01,366
This left them a bit concerned.

289
00:21:02,466 --> 00:21:05,233
How do you host the leader of such a major
nation

290
00:21:05,233 --> 00:21:07,533
at the White House without serving food?

291
00:21:08,733 --> 00:21:11,633
When we sat down, they brought me a glass
of hot water.

292
00:21:12,466 --> 00:21:16,200
I turned to President Obama and jokingly
said,

293
00:21:16,733 --> 00:21:20,033
"Look, my dinner has arrived!"

294
00:21:20,233 --> 00:21:22,433
as I placed the glass in front of me.

295
00:21:23,466 --> 00:21:26,466
Later, when I visited again, he still
remembered.

296
00:21:27,500 --> 00:21:30,833
He smiled and said, "Last time, you were
fasting."

297
00:21:31,233 --> 00:21:33,366
This time, we're having lunch

298
00:21:33,500 --> 00:21:36,766
Since you're not fasting, you’ll have to
eat twice as much!

299
00:21:38,266 --> 00:21:39,766
- Let's go to the beginning.

300
00:21:40,100 --> 00:21:44,366
You rose from humble beginnings to lead
the world's largest democracy.

301
00:21:44,766 --> 00:21:48,200
So, I think there's a lot of people for
whom this is truly inspiring.

302
00:21:48,800 --> 00:21:55,500
Your family was of very modest means, and
you grew up in a one-room house

303
00:21:56,000 --> 00:21:59,066
with a mud floor, your whole family living
there.

304
00:21:59,566 --> 00:22:01,266
Tell me about your childhood.

305
00:22:01,566 --> 00:22:04,966
How did those humble beginnings shape your
outlook on life?

306
00:22:07,066 --> 00:22:10,166
- My birthplace is in Gujarat,

307
00:22:11,666 --> 00:22:15,866
specifically in North Gujarat, in Mehsana
District,

308
00:22:16,766 --> 00:22:19,066
in a small town called Vadnagar.

309
00:22:20,966 --> 00:22:24,266
Historically, this town holds great
significance.

310
00:22:24,666 --> 00:22:29,700
And so, Vadnagar is where I was born and
completed my early education.

311
00:22:30,900 --> 00:22:37,200
Looking at the world as I
understand it today,

312
00:22:39,800 --> 00:22:44,666
I can reflect on my childhood and
the unique environment I grew up in.

313
00:22:49,733 --> 00:22:53,800
My village had certain fascinating
aspects,

314
00:22:53,833 --> 00:22:57,766
some of which are quite rare,
even globally.

315
00:23:01,233 --> 00:23:07,300
When I was in school, there was an elder
in our village

316
00:23:08,500 --> 00:23:14,433
who would regularly tell students,
"Listen, kids, wherever you go,

317
00:23:15,133 --> 00:23:16,600
if you find

318
00:23:18,333 --> 00:23:24,433
a carved stone or you find a
stone with inscriptions on it,

319
00:23:24,466 --> 00:23:29,033
or anything with engravings, bring it and
place it in this corner of the school.

320
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:34,366
Over time, my curiosity grew, and I
started to understand, I realized that

321
00:23:34,600 --> 00:23:37,200
my village had a rich and ancient history.

322
00:23:38,233 --> 00:23:43,300
Discussions at school often revealed more
fascinating details about its past.

323
00:23:45,433 --> 00:23:48,100
Later, I learned that China even made a
film about it.

324
00:23:49,000 --> 00:23:52,200
I had read in a newspaper about a film
that mentioned

325
00:23:52,600 --> 00:23:55,033
the Chinese philosopher Hiuen Tsang,

326
00:23:55,533 --> 00:23:58,600
who had spent a considerable amount of
time in my village,

327
00:23:59,633 --> 00:24:01,900
having arrived there many centuries ago.

328
00:24:03,066 --> 00:24:06,300
Back then, it was a major center for
Buddhist learning.

329
00:24:07,500 --> 00:24:10,500
That’s how I first learned about it.

330
00:24:11,700 --> 00:24:17,133
And perhaps, around the 1400s,

331
00:24:17,900 --> 00:24:20,900
it was a
prominent Buddhist educational hub.

332
00:24:21,900 --> 00:24:24,900
There was a Victory Monument from the 12th
century,

333
00:24:26,400 --> 00:24:30,133
a temple from the 17th century,

334
00:24:31,433 --> 00:24:35,833
and in the 16th century, two sisters, Tana
and Riri,

335
00:24:36,100 --> 00:24:39,233
who were renowned musicians.

336
00:24:40,833 --> 00:24:46,500
As I uncovered these history traces, I
grasped the depth of our heritage.

337
00:24:46,900 --> 00:24:52,100
So, when I became Chief Minister, I
initiated large-scale excavation projects.

338
00:24:53,300 --> 00:24:58,433
The findings from these very projects
confirmed

339
00:24:58,633 --> 00:25:05,600
that thousands of Buddhist monks
had, at one time, studied there.

340
00:25:06,933 --> 00:25:12,933
It was a place where Buddhist, Jain, and
Hindu traditions coexisted harmoniously.

341
00:25:14,900 --> 00:25:21,000
And, for us, history wasn’t just confined
to books.

342
00:25:23,200 --> 00:25:28,000
Every stone spoke, every wall had a story
to tell.

343
00:25:28,866 --> 00:25:33,400
And so when we began the large-scale
excavation work,

344
00:25:35,100 --> 00:25:39,000
we uncovered findings that hold immense
historical significance.

345
00:25:39,033 --> 00:25:45,700
So far, they have discovered evidence
dating back 2,800 years,

346
00:25:45,866 --> 00:25:51,700
proving that this city has remained
unbroken

347
00:25:52,333 --> 00:25:56,466
and eternal for all those 2800
years.

348
00:25:56,733 --> 00:26:03,133
They have discovered solid proof of how
its development unfolded over these
centuries.

349
00:26:03,633 --> 00:26:09,233
Now, an international-level museum has
been established there, open to visitors

350
00:26:10,333 --> 00:26:16,366
Especially for archaeology students, it
has become a major area of study.

351
00:26:16,500 --> 00:26:22,666
So, the place where I was born holds its
own unique historical significance.

352
00:26:23,133 --> 00:26:27,733
I see it as my good fortune; some things
in life unfold beyond our understanding.

353
00:26:28,166 --> 00:26:30,166
Kashi became my realm of duty.

354
00:26:30,700 --> 00:26:36,533
Now Kashi is also eternal. Kashi, also
known as Banaras or Varanasi,

355
00:26:36,766 --> 00:26:40,200
is an eternal city that has

356
00:26:41,266 --> 00:26:44,133
remained
vibrant and alive for centuries.

357
00:26:44,800 --> 00:26:50,600
Perhaps, it was some divine design that
led a boy born in Vadnagar

358
00:26:50,833 --> 00:26:54,700
to eventually make Kashi his realm of
duty,

359
00:26:54,900 --> 00:26:58,100
living in the embrace of Mother
Ganga.

360
00:26:59,433 --> 00:27:04,066
When I think about my family, my father,
my mother,

361
00:27:04,100 --> 00:27:07,333
my siblings, my uncles, aunts,
grandparents,

362
00:27:07,766 --> 00:27:11,700
we all grew up together in a
small house.

363
00:27:13,000 --> 00:27:17,700
The place we lived was likely even smaller
than where we are sitting now.

364
00:27:19,400 --> 00:27:22,333
There was no window, just a small door.

365
00:27:23,233 --> 00:27:25,533
That’s where I was born, that’s where I
grew up.

366
00:27:28,800 --> 00:27:31,700
Now, when people talk about poverty,

367
00:27:32,666 --> 00:27:36,300
it’s natural to discuss it in the context
of public life.

368
00:27:36,333 --> 00:27:41,533
And by those standards, my early life was
spent in extreme poverty.

369
00:27:42,333 --> 00:27:49,000
But we never really felt the burden of
poverty.

370
00:27:50,100 --> 00:27:54,400
You see, someone who is used to wearing
fine shoes

371
00:27:55,233 --> 00:27:59,300
will feel their absence when they don’t
have them.

372
00:27:59,700 --> 00:28:03,166
But for us, we had never worn shoes in our
lives,

373
00:28:03,433 --> 00:28:07,500
so how would we even know that wearing
shoes was a big deal?

374
00:28:08,100 --> 00:28:11,033
We weren’t in a position to compare.

375
00:28:11,200 --> 00:28:12,833
That’s just how we lived.

376
00:28:13,533 --> 00:28:16,466
Our mother worked incredibly hard.

377
00:28:16,866 --> 00:28:21,666
My father, too.
He was extremely hardworking.

378
00:28:22,600 --> 00:28:25,000
And he was also extremely disciplined.

379
00:28:25,866 --> 00:28:29,733
Every morning, around 4:00 or 4:30 AM, he
would leave the house,

380
00:28:30,600 --> 00:28:35,600
walk long distances, visit several
temples, and then reach his shop.

381
00:28:39,066 --> 00:28:43,400
He wore traditional leather shoes,
handmade in the village.

382
00:28:45,833 --> 00:28:48,766
The shoes were very tough and sturdy,

383
00:28:48,966 --> 00:28:53,000
making a distinct ‘tok tok tok’ sound when
he walked.

384
00:28:53,700 --> 00:28:56,300
People in the village used to say

385
00:28:57,200 --> 00:29:00,300
that they could tell the time
just by hearing his footsteps,

386
00:29:00,600 --> 00:29:06,233
"Oh yes," they would say: "Mr. Damodar is
on his way!"

387
00:29:06,733 --> 00:29:12,666
Such was his discipline. He worked
tirelessly, late into the night.

388
00:29:13,533 --> 00:29:19,733
Our mother, too, ensured that we never
felt the struggles of our circumstances.

389
00:29:21,833 --> 00:29:23,833
But despite everything,

390
00:29:24,866 --> 00:29:28,600
these challenging circumstances of living
in scarcity

391
00:29:29,400 --> 00:29:32,366
never left a mark on our
minds.

392
00:29:33,233 --> 00:29:38,533
I remember, in school, the idea of wearing
shoes never even crossed my mind.

393
00:29:40,333 --> 00:29:44,333
One day, while I was on my way to school,
I ran into my uncle on the way.

394
00:29:46,600 --> 00:29:52,733
He saw me and was surprised, "Hey! You go
to school like this? Without shoes?"

395
00:29:53,700 --> 00:29:58,533
So at that time, he bought me a pair of
canvas shoes and made me wear them.

396
00:30:00,433 --> 00:30:04,333
Back then, they must have cost around 10
or 12 rupees.

397
00:30:06,466 --> 00:30:09,033
But here's the thing,

398
00:30:10,366 --> 00:30:15,166
they were white canvas shoes,
and they would quickly get stained.

399
00:30:15,366 --> 00:30:16,633
So what did I do?

400
00:30:17,933 --> 00:30:24,333
In the evening, after school was over, I
would stay back for a while.

401
00:30:25,366 --> 00:30:28,266
I would go from classroom to classroom,

402
00:30:29,133 --> 00:30:33,933
collecting leftover pieces of chalk that
the teachers had discarded.

403
00:30:34,733 --> 00:30:37,433
I would take the pieces of chalk home,

404
00:30:38,100 --> 00:30:42,133
soak them in water, mix them into a paste,

405
00:30:42,900 --> 00:30:48,033
and polish my canvas shoes with it, making
them bright white again.

406
00:30:49,233 --> 00:30:53,433
For me, those shoes were a treasured
possession, a symbol of great wealth.

407
00:30:55,433 --> 00:30:57,333
And I don’t exactly know why,

408
00:30:57,466 --> 00:31:03,333
but from childhood, our mother was
extremely particular about cleanliness.

409
00:31:03,933 --> 00:31:06,833
Perhaps that’s where we inherited that
habit too.

410
00:31:08,133 --> 00:31:11,266
Not sure how I picked up the habit of
dressing neatly,

411
00:31:11,333 --> 00:31:12,733
but it’s been there since childhood.

412
00:31:13,333 --> 00:31:15,333
Whatever I wore, I made sure it looked
proper.

413
00:31:16,833 --> 00:31:23,033
Back then, as you can imagine, we didn’t
have any arrangements for ironing clothes.

414
00:31:23,666 --> 00:31:28,533
So instead, I would heat up water in a
copper pot,

415
00:31:28,733 --> 00:31:33,066
hold it with tongs, and press
my clothes myself.

416
00:31:33,633 --> 00:31:35,166
Then, I’d head off to school.

417
00:31:35,933 --> 00:31:38,966
That’s how I lived, and I found joy in it.

418
00:31:39,200 --> 00:31:43,633
We never thought about being poor, or
judged about how others lived,

419
00:31:43,666 --> 00:31:45,266
or what
their struggles were.

420
00:31:45,300 --> 00:31:51,533
We lived carefree, enjoying whatever
little we had, and kept working hard.

421
00:31:52,033 --> 00:31:54,400
Never once did we complain about these
things.

422
00:31:54,633 --> 00:32:01,533
And all these aspects of my life, whether
you call it fortune or misfortune,

423
00:32:02,233 --> 00:32:06,733
unfolded in such a way in politics that
they started coming to light.

424
00:32:06,933 --> 00:32:10,133
Because when I was taking my oath as Chief
Minister,

425
00:32:10,666 --> 00:32:14,400
TV reporters went to my village,
questioned my childhood friends,

426
00:32:14,466 --> 00:32:17,833
went to capture videos of my home.

427
00:32:18,533 --> 00:32:20,266
That’s when people started asking,

428
00:32:20,300 --> 00:32:23,066
"Who is this and what background
he is coming from?"

429
00:32:23,433 --> 00:32:28,433
Before that, very few knew much about my
life. That’s just how my journey has been.

430
00:32:30,733 --> 00:32:34,466
My mother possessed an innate spirit of
caring for others' well-being,

431
00:32:35,466 --> 00:32:38,666
it was woven into the very fabric of her
being.

432
00:32:39,633 --> 00:32:44,433
She possessed knowledge of traditional
remedies and healing practices

433
00:32:45,533 --> 00:32:48,433
and would
treat children with these remedies.

434
00:32:48,933 --> 00:32:53,933
Every morning, before sunrise, around five
o’clock, she would start treating them.

435
00:32:55,600 --> 00:32:58,366
So, all the children and their parents
would gather at our home,

436
00:32:58,500 --> 00:33:00,033
little children
crying,

437
00:33:00,066 --> 00:33:02,733
and we had to wake up early because of it.

438
00:33:03,833 --> 00:33:06,866
Meanwhile, my mother would continue
treating them with care.

439
00:33:07,033 --> 00:33:11,166
This spirit of service, in a way, was
nurtured through these experiences.

440
00:33:11,833 --> 00:33:16,066
A sense of empathy for society, the desire
to do good for others,

441
00:33:16,500 --> 00:33:21,566
these values were instilled in me from my
family.

442
00:33:23,933 --> 00:33:27,533
I believe that my life has been shaped by
my mother,

443
00:33:27,566 --> 00:33:32,933
my father, my teachers, and the
environment I grew up in.

444
00:33:33,666 --> 00:33:36,666
- There's a lot of young people listening
to this

445
00:33:36,866 --> 00:33:38,966
that are truly inspired by your
story.

446
00:33:39,633 --> 00:33:42,433
From those humble beginnings to

447
00:33:43,066 --> 00:33:46,833
the leader
of the biggest democracy in the world.

448
00:33:47,533 --> 00:33:51,433
What can you tell to those young folks,

449
00:33:51,933 --> 00:33:56,833
who are struggling, who are lost in the
world, who are trying to find their way,

450
00:33:57,533 --> 00:33:59,066
what advice could you give them?

451
00:33:59,800 --> 00:34:03,433
- I want to tell all young people the
following:

452
00:34:04,933 --> 00:34:11,933
No matter how dark the night may seem,

453
00:34:14,333 --> 00:34:19,933
it is still just night, and morning is
bound to come.

454
00:34:23,033 --> 00:34:29,866
That’s why we need patience and
self-confidence.

455
00:34:30,833 --> 00:34:36,066
Yes, the challenges are real, but I am not
defined by my circumstances.

456
00:34:37,233 --> 00:34:41,233
I am here for a purpose, sent by a higher
power.

457
00:34:41,666 --> 00:34:46,033
And I am not alone; the one who sent me is
always with me.

458
00:34:46,333 --> 00:34:49,633
This unwavering faith should always remain
within us.

459
00:34:50,166 --> 00:34:55,666
Difficulties are a test of endurance; they
are not meant to defeat me.

460
00:34:56,766 --> 00:34:59,200
Hardships exist to make me stronger,

461
00:34:59,700 --> 00:35:05,633
helping me grow and improve, not to leave
me hopeless or discouraged.

462
00:35:06,266 --> 00:35:11,833
Personally, I see every crisis, every
challenge, as an opportunity.

463
00:35:11,833 --> 00:35:13,333
So, to all young people, I say,

464
00:35:13,833 --> 00:35:16,866
"Have patience. There are no shortcuts in
life."

465
00:35:17,433 --> 00:35:20,633
At our railway stations, there hangs a
sign

466
00:35:21,833 --> 00:35:26,733
for those who habitually cross the tracks
instead of using the bridge.

467
00:35:26,933 --> 00:35:31,133
It reads, "Shortcut will cut you short."

468
00:35:31,133 --> 00:35:34,866
I would tell young people the same,
"Shortcut will cut you short."

469
00:35:34,933 --> 00:35:37,133
There are no shortcuts in life.

470
00:35:37,733 --> 00:35:40,500
Patience and perseverance are essential.

471
00:35:41,533 --> 00:35:46,333
Whatever responsibility we are given, we
must pour our heart into it.

472
00:35:46,733 --> 00:35:51,566
We should live it with passion, enjoy the
journey, and find fulfillment in it.

473
00:35:52,433 --> 00:35:57,166
I truly believe that if this mindset is
cultivated, it transforms life.

474
00:35:57,633 --> 00:36:03,133
Similarly, abundance alone is not enough,
there is no guarantee of success.

475
00:36:03,733 --> 00:36:07,466
Even a wealthy person who indulges in
comfort and idleness

476
00:36:07,666 --> 00:36:09,233
will eventually
wither away.

477
00:36:09,400 --> 00:36:13,366
Instead, he must decide, "Yes, I may have
resources around me,

478
00:36:13,666 --> 00:36:17,733
but I must use my abilities to grow them
further."

479
00:36:18,333 --> 00:36:22,566
I must contribute more to society with my
own strength.

480
00:36:23,033 --> 00:36:27,333
Even if I am in a good position, there is
still so much more to do.

481
00:36:27,500 --> 00:36:31,066
Even if I am not in a good position, there
is still so much work to do,

482
00:36:31,333 --> 00:36:33,000
that’s what I believe.

483
00:36:33,066 --> 00:36:35,933
I have also noticed that, some people tend
to think,

484
00:36:36,233 --> 00:36:38,233
"I've learned enough, that's it."

485
00:36:40,366 --> 00:36:44,666
But one should never let the student
within them die.

486
00:36:45,733 --> 00:36:48,133
Learning should never
stop.

487
00:36:48,833 --> 00:36:54,166
I believe that as long as I am alive, I
must have a purpose.

488
00:36:55,333 --> 00:37:00,566
Perhaps I exist to keep learning, to keep
growing.

489
00:37:02,433 --> 00:37:08,433
Now, my mother tongue
is Gujarati, and

490
00:37:10,433 --> 00:37:14,833
We were not very familiar with the Hindi
language,

491
00:37:17,266 --> 00:37:21,366
nor did we know how to speak it eloquently
or communicate effectively.

492
00:37:22,333 --> 00:37:25,500
But as a child, I used to sit at my
father’s tea shop.

493
00:37:25,933 --> 00:37:29,633
And at that young age, I got the chance to
meet so many people.

494
00:37:31,033 --> 00:37:34,133
And every time, I learned something from
them.

495
00:37:34,466 --> 00:37:39,666
I observed their ways of speaking, their
expressions, these things taught me a lot.

496
00:37:39,833 --> 00:37:43,366
Even though I wasn’t in a position to
apply it then,

497
00:37:43,433 --> 00:37:48,333
I thought, "If I ever get the chance, why
not?" "Why shouldn’t I present myself
well?"

498
00:37:48,933 --> 00:37:53,833
So, I believe the desire to learn should
always remain alive.

499
00:37:54,633 --> 00:37:59,266
And uh, another thing I’ve observed is
that most people

500
00:38:04,333 --> 00:38:10,800
dream about achieving something or
becoming someone. They set big targets,

501
00:38:12,166 --> 00:38:16,633
and when they fall short, they feel
disappointed.

502
00:38:18,933 --> 00:38:25,033
That’s why, whenever I get a chance to
talk to my friends, I tell them:

503
00:38:28,133 --> 00:38:33,333
"Instead of dreaming about getting and
becoming, dream of doing something."

504
00:38:34,433 --> 00:38:36,500
If you focus on 'DOING' something,

505
00:38:36,700 --> 00:38:40,533
and let’s say your goal is to reach ten,
but you make it to eight.

506
00:38:41,166 --> 00:38:44,733
you won’t feel discouraged. You’ll still
work toward ten with determination.

507
00:38:45,533 --> 00:38:49,633
But if your dream is only to become
something and it doesn’t happen,

508
00:38:49,766 --> 00:38:52,666
even your achievements may feel like a
burden.

509
00:38:53,133 --> 00:38:56,133
That’s why we must adjust our mindset in
life.

510
00:38:56,633 --> 00:38:59,933
Instead of thinking about what I got or
didn’t get,

511
00:39:00,366 --> 00:39:04,033
the mindset should be, "What
can I give?

512
00:39:05,766 --> 00:39:10,866
Because true contentment doesn’t bloom on
its own;

513
00:39:11,066 --> 00:39:15,133
it grows from the depths of what
you give.

514
00:39:16,566 --> 00:39:21,333
- And I should say that this young kid,
one of the things I dreamed of doing

515
00:39:21,533 --> 00:39:24,533
is to do this very thing to talk to you
today.

516
00:39:24,566 --> 00:39:26,466
So this is a very surreal.

517
00:39:26,833 --> 00:39:29,733
At 17, another fascinating part of your
life,

518
00:39:30,233 --> 00:39:33,933
you left home and spent two years roaming
in the Himalayas,

519
00:39:34,333 --> 00:39:38,166
searching for purpose, for deeper truth,
for God.

520
00:39:38,766 --> 00:39:41,233
So not much is known about this period of
your life.

521
00:39:41,433 --> 00:39:47,833
You lived a nomadic, minimalist existence
very much like a yogi.

522
00:39:48,433 --> 00:39:50,933
often sleeping without a roof on your head,

523
00:39:51,166 --> 00:39:57,966
what are some memorable spiritual moments,
rituals, experiences from that time?

524
00:39:59,666 --> 00:40:02,466
- It seems like you’ve put in a lot of
effort.

525
00:40:05,466 --> 00:40:06,766
Look, I ….

526
00:40:09,500 --> 00:40:12,900
Look, I don’t usually talk much about
this,

527
00:40:14,600 --> 00:40:17,766
but I can share a few external
aspects of it.

528
00:40:20,666 --> 00:40:23,333
I grew up in a very small town.

529
00:40:24,866 --> 00:40:27,800
Our life
was all about being part of a community.

530
00:40:30,500 --> 00:40:34,500
We lived among people, surrounded by them,
that was just how life was.

531
00:40:35,766 --> 00:40:40,166
There was a library in the village, and I
used to go there often to read books.

532
00:40:43,066 --> 00:40:48,333
Whenever I read something from the books,
I often found myself feeling inspired,

533
00:40:48,366 --> 00:40:53,566
thinking, why shouldn't I shape my own
life like that?

534
00:40:53,900 --> 00:40:55,700
That desire was always there.

535
00:40:56,400 --> 00:40:59,066
When I used to read about Swami
Vivekananda

536
00:40:59,166 --> 00:41:01,466
or read about Chhatrapati
Shivaji Maharaj,

537
00:41:01,600 --> 00:41:06,566
I would often wonder: how did they live?
How did they build such remarkable lives?

538
00:41:07,100 --> 00:41:11,100
And for that, I constantly experimented on
myself.

539
00:41:13,300 --> 00:41:19,066
Most of my experiments were physical in
nature, testing my body’s limits.

540
00:41:20,066 --> 00:41:23,500
For example, where I lived, winters
weren’t too harsh,

541
00:41:24,200 --> 00:41:27,066
but December nights could get quite cold.

542
00:41:28,366 --> 00:41:34,766
But still, at night

543
00:41:38,500 --> 00:41:40,566
the cold would bite, it was natural.

544
00:41:41,466 --> 00:41:48,066
So, sometimes, I would decide to sleep
outside in the open,

545
00:41:48,666 --> 00:41:54,666
with nothing to cover myself, just to see
how my body endures the cold.

546
00:41:55,366 --> 00:41:59,266
So, from a very young age, I would often
experiment with my body,

547
00:41:59,800 --> 00:42:02,366
and uh, this became a regular thing for
me.

548
00:42:04,100 --> 00:42:08,500
For me, going to the library,

549
00:42:09,333 --> 00:42:13,400
reading extensively,
visiting the pond,

550
00:42:13,966 --> 00:42:19,166
washing the family’s clothes, and swimming
became part of my routine.

551
00:42:19,200 --> 00:42:21,900
Swimming was my main physical activity.

552
00:42:23,066 --> 00:42:26,300
All of these things were deeply connected
to my life.

553
00:42:27,966 --> 00:42:32,666
Later, as I read Vivekananda, I became
even more drawn to his teachings.

554
00:42:37,100 --> 00:42:42,700
One time, I read about Swami Vivekananda.
His mother was ill,

555
00:42:44,266 --> 00:42:50,300
so he went to Sri Ramakrishna Paramahamsa
for guidance.

556
00:42:51,366 --> 00:42:54,466
He would argue with him, debate with him.

557
00:42:56,500 --> 00:42:58,200
In his early days,

558
00:43:00,433 --> 00:43:06,966
he would often argue with him, questioning
everything intellectually.

559
00:43:09,966 --> 00:43:16,066
He said, “My mother is sick. If I were
earning, I could take better care of her.”

560
00:43:17,200 --> 00:43:20,566
Sri Ramakrishna said, "Don't bother me
with all this."

561
00:43:21,100 --> 00:43:25,133
Go to Goddess Kali. She is there.

562
00:43:26,366 --> 00:43:28,400
Ask her
for what you need.”

563
00:43:30,800 --> 00:43:32,633
And so,

564
00:43:33,266 --> 00:43:37,966
Swami Vivekananda went and
sat before Goddess Kali's idol for hours,

565
00:43:38,200 --> 00:43:42,533
and he
immersed himself into deep meditation.

566
00:43:42,933 --> 00:43:45,166
After a few hours, when he returned,

567
00:43:46,733 --> 00:43:50,366
Ramakrishna asked him, "So, did you
request the goddess?"

568
00:43:51,366 --> 00:43:55,533
Swami Vivekananda replied, "No, I didn’t."
Ramakrishna said, "Go again tomorrow.

569
00:43:56,666 --> 00:43:59,000
She will fulfill your request. Ask her!"

570
00:43:59,400 --> 00:44:02,000
He went the next day, and then again the
day after.

571
00:44:03,400 --> 00:44:05,400
But each time,

572
00:44:07,966 --> 00:44:09,966
he found himself

573
00:44:12,833 --> 00:44:18,466
unable to ask for anything. His mother was
unwell, and he needed help,

574
00:44:19,600 --> 00:44:25,100
but when he sat before Goddess Kali, he
was completely absorbed in her presence.

575
00:44:25,933 --> 00:44:29,300
And yet, he could not bring himself to ask
for anything.

576
00:44:29,500 --> 00:44:31,866
Each time, he returned empty-handed.

577
00:44:31,966 --> 00:44:36,666
He told Sri Ramakrishna, "I came back
empty-handed. I didn’t ask for anything."

578
00:44:38,266 --> 00:44:42,266
To stand before the Divine Goddess and not
be able to ask for anything,

579
00:44:44,200 --> 00:44:48,666
that moment, that experience, lit a flame
inside him.

580
00:44:49,966 --> 00:44:51,900
There was a spark in his life,

581
00:44:53,666 --> 00:44:57,533
and from
that came the spirit of giving.

582
00:45:01,366 --> 00:45:03,166
I believe that perhaps

583
00:45:06,466 --> 00:45:11,100
that small incident in Vivekananda's life
left an impression on me too,

584
00:45:12,800 --> 00:45:15,066
the thought of ‘What can I give to the
world?’

585
00:45:18,166 --> 00:45:20,700
Maybe true contentment comes from giving.

586
00:45:22,366 --> 00:45:26,633
If my heart is only filled with the hunger
to receive, that hunger will never end.

587
00:45:29,266 --> 00:45:34,666
And within that realization came the idea
of Shiva and living beings as one,

588
00:45:36,866 --> 00:45:40,366
If you wish to serve Shiva, serve all
living beings.

589
00:45:41,366 --> 00:45:44,566
Recognize the unity between the divine and
the living.

590
00:45:45,466 --> 00:45:48,800
True non-duality is experienced through
this realization.

591
00:45:50,733 --> 00:45:53,300
I would often lose myself in such
thoughts,

592
00:45:54,900 --> 00:45:57,566
my mind naturally drifting in that
direction.

593
00:45:58,366 --> 00:46:00,066
I remember an incident,

594
00:46:01,566 --> 00:46:04,066
in the neighborhood where we lived,

595
00:46:04,866 --> 00:46:09,700
just outside,
there was a Lord Shiva temple.

596
00:46:11,033 --> 00:46:12,966
One day, a saint came to stay there.

597
00:46:15,366 --> 00:46:20,833
So that saint used to engage in meditation
and spiritual practices.

598
00:46:21,066 --> 00:46:23,133
I started feeling drawn to him,

599
00:46:23,500 --> 00:46:26,366
thinking perhaps he possessed some
spiritual energy.

600
00:46:26,966 --> 00:46:32,600
I had only read about Swami Vivekananda,
never seen such figures in real life.

601
00:46:34,500 --> 00:46:37,400
During Navratri, he was fasting,

602
00:46:37,800 --> 00:46:43,166
and he had placed Sorghum grains on his
hand, a common tradition in our culture.

603
00:46:44,766 --> 00:46:47,133
In a way, sprouting seeds on your palms

604
00:46:47,166 --> 00:46:49,533
and sleeping like that for nine or ten
days.

605
00:46:50,066 --> 00:46:53,600
It was a kind of spiritual vow, and this
saint was observing it.

606
00:46:54,566 --> 00:46:56,700
During those same days,

607
00:46:56,900 --> 00:47:01,400
my maternal uncle’s family was
preparing for my aunt’s wedding.

608
00:47:01,466 --> 00:47:05,966
Everyone from my home was going to my
uncle’s house for the wedding.

609
00:47:07,233 --> 00:47:11,200
Now, for any child, visiting an uncle’s
house is always exciting.

610
00:47:11,766 --> 00:47:15,200
But I told my family, "I’m not going.
I’ll stay here,

611
00:47:15,400 --> 00:47:17,266
and I will take care of Swamiji."

612
00:47:17,800 --> 00:47:20,966
Since he has these grains on his hand, he
can't eat or drink.

613
00:47:20,966 --> 00:47:22,300
So, I will take care of him.

614
00:47:22,633 --> 00:47:25,633
So, as a child, I chose not to attend the
wedding.

615
00:47:25,666 --> 00:47:28,600
I stayed back, serving Swamiji instead.

616
00:47:29,166 --> 00:47:32,266
Somehow, my mind was naturally drawn in
that direction.

617
00:47:33,600 --> 00:47:38,866
At times, whenever soldiers from my
village came home during their holidays,

618
00:47:39,066 --> 00:47:42,166
They would walk around in their uniforms
with such pride.

619
00:47:42,500 --> 00:47:47,766
I would run behind them all day, thinking,
"Look at them! They are serving the nation."

620
00:47:48,166 --> 00:47:53,700
So there was always a strong feeling
inside me to do something meaningful.

621
00:47:54,266 --> 00:47:59,200
I didn’t fully understand what it would
be, and I didn’t have a roadmap.

622
00:47:59,966 --> 00:48:01,700
There was a hunger within me,

623
00:48:01,900 --> 00:48:05,800
a deep longing to understand life,
to explore its meaning.

624
00:48:05,900 --> 00:48:10,000
So, I just set out and
began the journey.

625
00:48:11,300 --> 00:48:13,300
During my time in the mission,

626
00:48:14,300 --> 00:48:18,766
I came across remarkable saints. They
showered me with love and blessings.

627
00:48:19,066 --> 00:48:22,666
Among them, I formed a special bond with
Swami Atmasthananda Ji.

628
00:48:22,833 --> 00:48:26,200
He lived for nearly a hundred years, a
life full of wisdom and service.

629
00:48:26,766 --> 00:48:28,466
In his final years,

630
00:48:28,733 --> 00:48:32,700
I deeply wished for him to stay with me at
the Prime Minister’s residence.

631
00:48:32,833 --> 00:48:36,066
But his responsibilities were vast, and he
couldn’t come.

632
00:48:36,100 --> 00:48:39,133
However, back when I was Chief Minister,
he used to visit,

633
00:48:39,333 --> 00:48:42,766
and I was fortunate to receive his
blessings and guidance.

634
00:48:42,966 --> 00:48:45,266
He once looked at me and said,

635
00:48:49,200 --> 00:48:53,333
"Why have you come here? You have a
greater purpose to fulfill."

636
00:48:55,200 --> 00:49:00,366
"Is your priority your own well-being, or
is it the welfare of society?"

637
00:49:01,133 --> 00:49:05,100
Whatever Swami Vivekananda said was for
the betterment of society.

638
00:49:06,266 --> 00:49:08,200
He said, "You are meant to serve others."

639
00:49:09,566 --> 00:49:10,566
So I….

640
00:49:12,866 --> 00:49:16,200
I remember feeling a bit disheartened at
that moment,

641
00:49:16,233 --> 00:49:19,666
I had come seeking guidance, but all I got
were words.

642
00:49:20,500 --> 00:49:24,066
So, I continued on my journey, wandering
from place to place.

643
00:49:24,400 --> 00:49:29,166
I spent time in the Himalayas, embracing
the solitude of the mountains.

644
00:49:29,900 --> 00:49:32,900
I met many remarkable individuals along
the way,

645
00:49:33,033 --> 00:49:37,566
some were great ascetics, people who had
renounced everything.

646
00:49:38,066 --> 00:49:40,700
But still, my mind remained
restless.

647
00:49:41,066 --> 00:49:46,666
Perhaps it was my age of curiosity, of
wanting to learn, to understand.

648
00:49:48,066 --> 00:49:50,066
It was a new experience,

649
00:49:50,566 --> 00:49:56,466
a world shaped by the mountains, by ice,
by the towering snow-covered peaks.

650
00:49:57,100 --> 00:49:59,666
But all of this played a huge role in
shaping me.

651
00:50:01,000 --> 00:50:06,266
It strengthened me from within and enabled
me to discover my inner power.

652
00:50:06,866 --> 00:50:11,266
Practicing meditation, waking up in the
sacred pre-dawn hours,

653
00:50:11,300 --> 00:50:15,200
bathing in the cold,
serving people with devotion,

654
00:50:15,466 --> 00:50:20,666
and naturally tending to elderly saints,
became a seamless part of who I was.

655
00:50:21,566 --> 00:50:24,500
Once, a natural calamity struck the region,

656
00:50:25,266 --> 00:50:28,466
and I immediately devoted myself
to helping the villagers.

657
00:50:29,166 --> 00:50:32,300
So these were the saints and spiritual
masters

658
00:50:32,666 --> 00:50:34,766
with whom I stayed from time to
time.

659
00:50:36,166 --> 00:50:40,766
I never remained in one place for long. I
kept moving, constantly wandering.

660
00:50:42,366 --> 00:50:44,166
That was the kind of life I lived.

661
00:50:45,400 --> 00:50:52,066
- And for people who don't know that
moment in Ramakrishna mission ashram with

662
00:50:52,400 --> 00:50:55,766
with the monk Swami Atmasthananda, as you
mentioned.

663
00:50:56,066 --> 00:51:00,266
He helped steer you towards the life of
service.

664
00:51:00,566 --> 00:51:05,766
So there is another possible life that
could have been where you take sanyasa,

665
00:51:05,800 --> 00:51:08,400
you give away everything and you are a
monk.

666
00:51:09,166 --> 00:51:13,566
So we could have had a monk Narendra Modi
and a prime minister Narendra Modi.

667
00:51:13,600 --> 00:51:19,500
And he helped you take the decision to
live a life of service at every scale.

668
00:51:21,066 --> 00:51:26,166
- From the outside, people may call me a
leader, some call me the Prime Minister,

669
00:51:26,566 --> 00:51:28,933
others call me the Chief Minister,

670
00:51:29,233 --> 00:51:31,800
and that's how they see me
from their perspective.

671
00:51:34,100 --> 00:51:39,066
But deep within, there is only an
unwavering spiritual commitment.

672
00:51:40,066 --> 00:51:45,700
The Modi who lovingly helped his mother
care for children during their treatments,

673
00:51:45,900 --> 00:51:48,900
tending to them with patience and
compassion,

674
00:51:51,866 --> 00:51:54,500
the Modi who wandered through the
Himalayas,

675
00:51:55,033 --> 00:51:59,833
and the Modi who now works from this seat
of responsibility,

676
00:52:00,400 --> 00:52:04,166
they are all tied together by the same
inner consistency.

677
00:52:05,066 --> 00:52:08,766
Every action is dedicated to serving
others.

678
00:52:10,433 --> 00:52:14,666
People may see a stark difference between
a saint and a leader

679
00:52:14,700 --> 00:52:16,933
but to me, there is no real difference.

680
00:52:17,533 --> 00:52:20,666
Yes, the attire changes, the way of life
changes,

681
00:52:20,700 --> 00:52:23,400
the words spoken throughout
the day shift,

682
00:52:23,600 --> 00:52:25,700
and the nature of work evolves.

683
00:52:25,900 --> 00:52:28,566
But the core of my being remains
unchanged,

684
00:52:28,700 --> 00:52:33,433
carrying out every responsibility with
the same sense of calm focus and dedication.

685
00:52:33,766 --> 00:52:38,266
- Another part of your life of who you are
is you've spoken your whole life

686
00:52:38,266 --> 00:52:41,600
about putting your nation of India above
all else.

687
00:52:41,966 --> 00:52:44,300
When you were eight, you joined the RSS,

688
00:52:44,666 --> 00:52:47,966
which espouses the idea of Hindu
nationalism.

689
00:52:48,566 --> 00:52:52,066
Can you tell me about RSS and what impact
they had on

690
00:52:53,000 --> 00:52:56,966
who you are and the development of your
political ideas?

691
00:52:57,966 --> 00:52:59,266
- Ever since childhood,

692
00:53:01,700 --> 00:53:05,400
I always had the habit of staying engaged
in something or the other.

693
00:53:06,400 --> 00:53:11,766
I remember there was a man named Makoshi,
I don’t quite recall his full name,

694
00:53:11,766 --> 00:53:16,266
I think he was part of the service group,
Makoshi Soni or something like that.

695
00:53:17,866 --> 00:53:21,900
He used to carry a small drum-like
instrument called a tambourine with him.

696
00:53:22,566 --> 00:53:26,966
And he used to sing patriotic songs in his
deep, powerful voice.

697
00:53:27,366 --> 00:53:31,900
Whenever he came to our village, he would
hold programs in different places.

698
00:53:32,566 --> 00:53:36,200
I would run after him like a crazy fan,
just to listen to his songs.

699
00:53:37,100 --> 00:53:41,666
I would spend entire nights listening to
their patriotic songs. I enjoyed it

700
00:53:41,700 --> 00:53:43,500
I don’t even know why, but I just did.

701
00:53:43,866 --> 00:53:47,500
In our village there was a branch of the
Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh,

702
00:53:48,000 --> 00:53:50,700
where we played sports and sang patriotic
songs.

703
00:53:51,233 --> 00:53:55,566
Something about those songs touched me
deeply; they stirred something inside me.

704
00:53:56,033 --> 00:53:59,133
And that’s how I eventually became part of
the RSS.

705
00:54:00,000 --> 00:54:03,966
One of the core values that were
instilled in us at RSS was

706
00:54:05,966 --> 00:54:08,166
whatever you do, do it with a
purpose.

707
00:54:08,300 --> 00:54:11,633
Even while studying, study with the goal
of learning enough

708
00:54:11,666 --> 00:54:13,166
to contribute to the
nation.

709
00:54:14,400 --> 00:54:16,466
Even when you exercise, do it with the

710
00:54:16,500 --> 00:54:19,066
purpose of strengthening your body to
serve the nation.

711
00:54:19,300 --> 00:54:24,666
This is what we were taught. And today,
RSS is a massive organization.

712
00:54:24,866 --> 00:54:28,566
It is now nearing its 100th anniversary.

713
00:54:29,266 --> 00:54:31,500
Such a massive volunteer organization

714
00:54:32,000 --> 00:54:36,400
likely doesn’t exist anywhere else in the
world

715
00:54:38,166 --> 00:54:40,700
Millions of people are connected to it.

716
00:54:41,966 --> 00:54:45,966
But understanding RSS is not that simple.

717
00:54:47,700 --> 00:54:50,933
One must make an effort to truly grasp the
nature of its work.

718
00:54:52,633 --> 00:54:54,533
More than anything,

719
00:54:57,733 --> 00:55:00,233
the RSS provides you
with a clear direction

720
00:55:00,866 --> 00:55:04,166
toward what can truly be called a purpose
in life.

721
00:55:04,933 --> 00:55:10,566
Secondly, the nation is everything, and
serving the people is akin to serving God.

722
00:55:11,366 --> 00:55:13,766
This is what has been said since the Vedic
era,

723
00:55:13,766 --> 00:55:18,766
what our sages have said, what Vivekananda
said, and what the RSS echoes.

724
00:55:20,366 --> 00:55:24,166
A volunteer is told that the inspiration
he gains from RSS,

725
00:55:24,866 --> 00:55:29,366
it’s not just about attending the one-hour
session or wearing the uniform.

726
00:55:29,566 --> 00:55:32,266
What matters is what you do for society.

727
00:55:32,533 --> 00:55:36,233
And today, inspired by that spirit, many
initiatives are thriving.

728
00:55:36,666 --> 00:55:40,666
Like some volunteers established an
organization called Seva Bharti.

729
00:55:41,200 --> 00:55:45,933
This organization serves the slums and
settlements where the poorest people live,

730
00:55:46,666 --> 00:55:48,800
which they call service communities.

731
00:55:50,200 --> 00:55:51,600
To my knowledge,

732
00:55:52,333 --> 00:55:53,966
they run approximately

733
00:55:54,766 --> 00:55:58,033
one hundred and
twenty-five thousand service projects,

734
00:55:58,433 --> 00:56:03,200
without any government assistance,
solely through community support.

735
00:56:03,700 --> 00:56:07,366
They spend time there,
teach the children,

736
00:56:07,866 --> 00:56:11,566
care for their health,
instill good values,

737
00:56:12,433 --> 00:56:15,533
and work towards improving cleanliness in
these communities.

738
00:56:15,666 --> 00:56:19,766
Running 125,000 social service projects is
no small feat.

739
00:56:20,000 --> 00:56:25,033
Similarly, some volunteers, nurtured by
RSS,

740
00:56:25,266 --> 00:56:29,666
are dedicated to serving tribal
communities through Vanvasi Kalyan Ashram.

741
00:56:29,766 --> 00:56:34,233
They live among the tribal people, working
for their welfare.

742
00:56:34,266 --> 00:56:39,466
They have established over 70,000 one
teacher schools, in remote tribal regions.

743
00:56:39,966 --> 00:56:44,766
There are also some people in America who
show there support for this cause,

744
00:56:45,300 --> 00:56:49,766
and contribute donations of
about $10 or $15.

745
00:56:50,066 --> 00:56:55,566
And they say, ‘Skip a Coca-Cola
this month, don't drink Coca-cola

746
00:56:55,766 --> 00:56:59,033
and donate that money to a One Teacher
school instead.

747
00:56:59,233 --> 00:57:04,300
Now imagine, 70,000 one teacher schools
dedicated to educating tribal children.

748
00:57:05,266 --> 00:57:10,466
Some volunteers have founded
Vidya Bharati to revolutionize education.

749
00:57:11,766 --> 00:57:14,700
Today, they run nearly 25,000 schools,

750
00:57:15,466 --> 00:57:17,733
educating around 3 million students,

751
00:57:18,633 --> 00:57:22,600
and I believe that millions of students
have benefited from this initiative,

752
00:57:23,233 --> 00:57:27,366
receiving quality education at an
incredibly low cost.

753
00:57:28,466 --> 00:57:32,866
Alongside education, values are
prioritized, and students remain grounded,

754
00:57:33,066 --> 00:57:36,700
learning skills so they don’t become a
burden on society.

755
00:57:37,166 --> 00:57:40,066
That is, in every aspect of life,

756
00:57:40,600 --> 00:57:45,766
whether it’s women, youth, or even
laborers, the RSS has played a role.

757
00:57:46,300 --> 00:57:51,566
In terms of membership size, if I may say
so, we have The Indian Labor Union.

758
00:57:52,366 --> 00:57:57,433
It has around 50,000 unions,

759
00:57:58,466 --> 00:58:00,900
with millions
of members across the country.

760
00:58:01,133 --> 00:58:04,866
Perhaps, in terms of scale, there is no
bigger labor union in the world.

761
00:58:05,666 --> 00:58:07,866
But what’s interesting is the approach
they take.

762
00:58:11,266 --> 00:58:12,366
Historically,

763
00:58:13,933 --> 00:58:17,533
leftist ideologies have
fueled labor movements worldwide.

764
00:58:18,166 --> 00:58:20,766
And what has been their slogan?

765
00:58:21,866 --> 00:58:23,766
"Workers of the world, unite!"

766
00:58:24,766 --> 00:58:29,600
The message was clear, unite first, and
then we’ll deal with everything else.

767
00:58:30,266 --> 00:58:34,700
But what do the labor unions run by
RSS-trained volunteers believe in?

768
00:58:35,266 --> 00:58:39,566
They say, "Workers unite the world."

769
00:58:42,100 --> 00:58:46,833
Others say, "Workers of the World Unite."

770
00:58:46,866 --> 00:58:49,966
and we say "Workers Unite the World."

771
00:58:51,300 --> 00:58:54,766
It may seem like just a small shift in
words,

772
00:58:54,766 --> 00:58:57,400
but it represents a huge ideological
transformation.

773
00:58:58,000 --> 00:59:00,633
The volunteers who come from the RSS

774
00:59:01,066 --> 00:59:04,366
follow their own interests,
nature, and inclination

775
00:59:04,766 --> 00:59:08,366
and in doing so, they strengthen and
promote these kinds of activities.

776
00:59:08,800 --> 00:59:11,200
When you observe these initiatives,

777
00:59:11,766 --> 00:59:16,566
you’ll see how, over the past hundred
years, the RSS

778
00:59:17,466 --> 00:59:19,333
has dedicated itself

779
00:59:20,733 --> 00:59:23,500
with the discipline
and devotion of a seeker,

780
00:59:24,500 --> 00:59:28,633
staying away from the glare of mainstream
attention.

781
00:59:29,166 --> 00:59:34,933
I feel blessed to gain life’s values from
such a sacred organization.

782
00:59:36,133 --> 00:59:38,566
Through the RSS, I found a life of
purpose.

783
00:59:39,366 --> 00:59:45,266
Then, I was fortunate to spend some time
among the saints,

784
00:59:45,666 --> 00:59:48,166
which gave me a strong spiritual
foundation.

785
00:59:48,900 --> 00:59:53,466
I found discipline and a life of purpose

786
00:59:53,566 --> 00:59:56,966
and through the guidance of saints, I
gained spiritual grounding.

787
00:59:56,966 --> 01:00:01,033
Swami Atmasthananda and others like him
have held my hand throughout my journey,

788
01:00:01,366 --> 01:00:03,466
constantly guiding me at every step.

789
01:00:03,900 --> 01:00:09,733
The teachings of Ramakrishna Mission,
Swami Vivekananda,

790
01:00:10,166 --> 01:00:13,300
and the service-driven philosophy of the
RSS

791
01:00:13,766 --> 01:00:16,866
have played a crucial role in shaping me.

792
01:00:17,566 --> 01:00:21,966
- But they've also helped push the idea of
India.

793
01:00:22,466 --> 01:00:28,966
What is the idea that unifies India? What
is India as a nation?

794
01:00:29,466 --> 01:00:32,400
What is the foundational idea that unites

795
01:00:32,866 --> 01:00:38,533
all of these disparate worlds and
communities and cultures?

796
01:00:38,566 --> 01:00:39,966
What would it be?

797
01:00:40,600 --> 01:00:46,600
- Look, India is a cultural identity.

798
01:00:49,900 --> 01:00:55,966
It is a civilization that dates back
thousands of years.

799
01:00:57,666 --> 01:00:59,666
Consider the vastness of India,

800
01:01:00,500 --> 01:01:02,533
over a hundred languages,

801
01:01:04,466 --> 01:01:05,866
thousands of dialects.

802
01:01:07,866 --> 01:01:10,700
India is so diverse that we have a saying,

803
01:01:11,266 --> 01:01:14,700
that every twenty miles the language
changes.

804
01:01:15,200 --> 01:01:18,066
Customs change, cuisine changes,

805
01:01:18,466 --> 01:01:21,300
even clothing styles shift
from region to region.

806
01:01:22,066 --> 01:01:27,866
From the south to the north, you will see
immense diversity across the country.

807
01:01:28,533 --> 01:01:30,800
But if you dig a little deeper,

808
01:01:31,233 --> 01:01:36,000
you will
find a common thread.

809
01:01:36,233 --> 01:01:40,066
For example, the stories of Lord Ram can
be heard everywhere in India.

810
01:01:40,300 --> 01:01:42,666
His name echoes in every corner of the
country.

811
01:01:43,033 --> 01:01:44,866
But if you look closely,

812
01:01:46,033 --> 01:01:49,600
from Tamil Nadu
to Jammu and Kashmir,

813
01:01:50,333 --> 01:01:54,500
you will always find people whose names
include ‘Ram’ in some form.

814
01:01:58,333 --> 01:02:00,566
In Gujarat, he might be called ‘Ram Bhai,’

815
01:02:00,766 --> 01:02:03,300
in Tamil Nadu, ‘Ramachandran,’

816
01:02:04,066 --> 01:02:06,666
in
Maharashtra, ‘Ram Bhau.’

817
01:02:07,633 --> 01:02:13,166
This unique cultural bond is what unites
India as one civilization,

818
01:02:13,866 --> 01:02:18,000
Take something as simple as

819
01:02:19,266 --> 01:02:21,166
bathing in water.

820
01:02:21,800 --> 01:02:23,333
We have a ritual

821
01:02:25,133 --> 01:02:27,600
where all the rivers of
India are remembered.

822
01:02:28,266 --> 01:02:33,000
They chant: "I am bathing
with the waters of all these
rivers."

823
01:02:33,133 --> 01:02:42,700
Ganga, Yamuna, Godavari, Saraswati,
Narmada, Sindhu, Kaveri,

824
01:02:42,966 --> 01:02:47,700
It's a sentiment that unites a nation. And
we have a long tradition of

825
01:02:48,400 --> 01:02:52,600
making such resolutions at the beginning
of important events and rituals.

826
01:02:53,766 --> 01:02:57,666
And the resolution itself can present a
historical record.

827
01:02:59,166 --> 01:03:04,000
And, in so doing, serve as a way of
collecting and preserving historical data.

828
01:03:04,200 --> 01:03:08,933
It has been an incredibly unique system,
guided meticulously by our scriptures.

829
01:03:09,066 --> 01:03:13,266
When someone makes a resolution performs a
puja, or even during weddings,

830
01:03:13,366 --> 01:03:15,666
we start by invoking the entire universe,

831
01:03:15,866 --> 01:03:20,533
beginning with Jambudweep, Bharatkhand,
Aryavrat,

832
01:03:20,766 --> 01:03:23,433
and gradually narrow it down to the
village,

833
01:03:23,633 --> 01:03:25,733
then mentioning the specific
family,

834
01:03:26,666 --> 01:03:29,566
and finally, we invoke the family deity.

835
01:03:30,066 --> 01:03:34,200
This practice is still alive, happening
daily in every corner of India.

836
01:03:36,033 --> 01:03:40,066
But sadly, the Western and global models
began viewing nations

837
01:03:40,666 --> 01:03:43,066
only as administrative systems.

838
01:03:43,366 --> 01:03:47,933
India, however, has had a variety of
administrative systems throughout history.

839
01:03:47,966 --> 01:03:51,566
Many systems were fragmented, scattered,
and varied across regions.

840
01:03:51,600 --> 01:03:53,833
Kings and rulers were numerous,

841
01:03:54,033 --> 01:03:58,166
but India's unity lay
in cultural bonds.

842
01:03:58,233 --> 01:04:01,933
Pilgrimage traditions played a key role in
preserving this unity.

843
01:04:02,133 --> 01:04:05,266
Shankaracharya established the four
pilgrimage sites.

844
01:04:05,366 --> 01:04:09,700
Even today, millions of people travel from
one place to another for pilgrimage.

845
01:04:10,066 --> 01:04:15,900
In Kashi, you’ll find people who bring
water from Rameshwaram to Kashi

846
01:04:15,966 --> 01:04:18,066
and take water from Kashi to Rameshwaram.

847
01:04:18,600 --> 01:04:22,566
Even if you look at our Hindu calendar,

848
01:04:22,600 --> 01:04:26,166
you’ll find so many things across the
country that you can’t even imagine.

849
01:04:27,600 --> 01:04:32,066
- If we look at the historical foundation
of modern India,

850
01:04:33,466 --> 01:04:37,066
along with yourself, Mahatma Gandhi is

851
01:04:37,266 --> 01:04:41,966
one of the most important humans
to have ever lived.

852
01:04:42,400 --> 01:04:45,900
But certainly one of the most important
humans to the history of India.

853
01:04:46,800 --> 01:04:51,400
What do you admire about Mahatma Gandhi?

854
01:04:54,933 --> 01:04:56,866
- As I had mentioned before,

855
01:04:57,433 --> 01:05:01,866
I was born in Gujarat,
and Gujarati is my mother tongue.

856
01:05:02,900 --> 01:05:09,066
Mahatma Gandhi was also born in Gujarat.
His native language was Gujarati, too.

857
01:05:10,500 --> 01:05:16,233
He pursued a career as an attorney and
lived overseas for several years.

858
01:05:17,100 --> 01:05:19,366
He had plenty of great opportunities.

859
01:05:21,833 --> 01:05:24,600
But the deep sense of duty within him,

860
01:05:25,200 --> 01:05:28,166
along with the values instilled
by his family,

861
01:05:28,633 --> 01:05:33,766
led him to give up all comforts and devote
his life to serving the people of India.

862
01:05:34,200 --> 01:05:37,000
He joined the struggle for India’s
independence.

863
01:05:40,166 --> 01:05:41,633
And to this day,

864
01:05:44,133 --> 01:05:46,500
he continues to deeply
influence

865
01:05:47,466 --> 01:05:50,066
the life of every Indian in some
way.

866
01:05:52,000 --> 01:05:56,700
Mahatma Gandhi tried to live by his
principles,

867
01:05:56,900 --> 01:05:58,666
and practiced what he
preached.

868
01:05:58,900 --> 01:06:04,666
For example, he strongly advocated for
cleanliness and practiced it himself.

869
01:06:05,400 --> 01:06:08,500
And he made it a point to discuss
cleanliness wherever he went.

870
01:06:09,400 --> 01:06:13,066
Another key factor to consider is India's
fight for independence.

871
01:06:15,366 --> 01:06:19,066
India was ruled by the Mughals,

872
01:06:19,700 --> 01:06:22,666
the British, and
several other foreign powers.

873
01:06:25,033 --> 01:06:30,100
Despite being bound by the shackles of
colonial rule for centuries,

874
01:06:32,100 --> 01:06:35,100
the flame of independence burned brightly

875
01:06:36,533 --> 01:06:43,300
in every corner and nook of India, never
fading, always fueling the desire for freedom.

876
01:06:44,500 --> 01:06:50,266
Millions of people sacrificed their lives
so the light of freedom could shine on India

877
01:06:50,566 --> 01:06:52,666
They laid down their lives for freedom,

878
01:06:52,666 --> 01:06:55,566
sacrificing their youth
behind prison walls.

879
01:06:56,433 --> 01:07:00,533
Mahatma Gandhi also fought for India’s
independence, but in his own way.

880
01:07:00,800 --> 01:07:05,266
Indeed, the other freedom fighters were
brave warriors,

881
01:07:05,466 --> 01:07:07,900
and devoted sons of Mother
India.

882
01:07:08,400 --> 01:07:11,200
They came, they fought, and their
martyrdom immortalized them.

883
01:07:12,466 --> 01:07:14,900
And they did indeed have a lasting impact.

884
01:07:15,366 --> 01:07:18,666
But it was Mahatma Gandhi who awakened a
nation,

885
01:07:18,866 --> 01:07:21,400
leading a mass movement fueled by
truth.

886
01:07:22,366 --> 01:07:26,566
And he wove even a sweeper into the very
fabric of the freedom struggle.

887
01:07:26,966 --> 01:07:29,966
He told teachers their work was part of
the freedom struggle.

888
01:07:30,266 --> 01:07:33,466
He told the people spinning thread and
weaving clothes

889
01:07:33,666 --> 01:07:35,066
they were freedom
fighters.

890
01:07:35,600 --> 01:07:39,866
He told those tending to lepers that their
service was a step toward India’s freedom.

891
01:07:40,300 --> 01:07:44,500
He viewed every task as a vital thread in
the fabric of India’s independence movement.

892
01:07:45,100 --> 01:07:50,200
And this transformed India's common man
into a soldier in the quest for freedom.

893
01:07:50,900 --> 01:07:56,866
Gandhi forged a mass movement so immense
that the British could never fully grasp it.

894
01:07:57,466 --> 01:08:03,633
The British never imagined that a pinch of
salt from the Dandi March

895
01:08:03,866 --> 01:08:07,566
could spark a massive revolution,
and he made it happen.

896
01:08:08,366 --> 01:08:13,100
And his life, presence, style, mannerisms,

897
01:08:13,400 --> 01:08:15,700
all left a profound impact.

898
01:08:16,266 --> 01:08:18,133
And I have seen

899
01:08:19,866 --> 01:08:24,266
many of his stories evolve
into timeless legends.

900
01:08:24,566 --> 01:08:27,666
I recall an incident from a Round Table
Conference.

901
01:08:29,300 --> 01:08:34,166
Yeah, I believe he was attending a Round
Table Conference.

902
01:08:36,233 --> 01:08:40,566
He was supposed to meet King George at the
Buckingham Palace.

903
01:08:41,300 --> 01:08:46,066
Draped in his breechcloth, Mahatma Gandhi
made his way to the palace.

904
01:08:47,366 --> 01:08:52,466
Many people were amazed that he had showed
up in that attire to meet the King.

905
01:08:54,866 --> 01:08:57,666
Gandhi remarked he didn’t need to wear a
lot of clothes.

906
01:08:58,266 --> 01:09:03,166
He said, "Your King is wearing enough
clothes for the both of us."

907
01:09:04,300 --> 01:09:06,466
This was the whimsical charm of his
nature.

908
01:09:07,266 --> 01:09:10,866
Mahatma Gandhi possessed many remarkable
qualities.

909
01:09:11,466 --> 01:09:16,700
His call for unity
and recognition of

910
01:09:17,733 --> 01:09:23,166
the people's strength
still resonates with me.

911
01:09:23,566 --> 01:09:29,366
In everything I do, I strive to include
the common man

912
01:09:31,166 --> 01:09:34,266
and to ensure the participation of as many
as possible.

913
01:09:35,800 --> 01:09:39,800
I don't believe in leaving everything to
the government.

914
01:09:41,166 --> 01:09:45,566
I am a firm believer in the power of
social change.

915
01:09:46,466 --> 01:09:53,200
- So, he was probably one of the greatest
leaders of the 20th century.

916
01:09:54,400 --> 01:09:57,766
You are one of the greatest leaders of the
21st century.

917
01:10:00,066 --> 01:10:02,400
Those two centuries are very different.

918
01:10:03,100 --> 01:10:09,066
And you have been masterful

919
01:10:09,533 --> 01:10:13,666
in the game,
in the art of geopolitics.

920
01:10:13,966 --> 01:10:17,300
So, let me ask you—you have found a
balance.

921
01:10:17,700 --> 01:10:21,933
So, when negotiating on the world stage
with super powerful nations,

922
01:10:22,566 --> 01:10:25,066
is it better to be loved or feared?

923
01:10:26,200 --> 01:10:31,766
It seems like you are a master class of
being loved by everybody,

924
01:10:32,100 --> 01:10:34,766
but everybody knows and feels the
strength.

925
01:10:35,600 --> 01:10:38,900
So, finding that balance—can you speak to
that balance?

926
01:10:40,800 --> 01:10:47,100
- First and foremost, I don't think this
is a fair comparison.

927
01:10:48,100 --> 01:10:52,200
Mahatma Gandhi wasn't just a

928
01:10:53,666 --> 01:10:56,500
twentieth-century leader.

929
01:10:56,966 --> 01:10:59,766
His relevance
transcends centuries.

930
01:11:00,066 --> 01:11:05,800
Mahatma Gandhi's legacy will last for
centuries to come,

931
01:11:06,066 --> 01:11:08,766
and he remains relevant
to date.

932
01:11:09,333 --> 01:11:12,866
As far as I am concerned, I have a
responsibility to fulfill.

933
01:11:14,166 --> 01:11:19,700
Yet, the weight of that responsibility
pales in comparison to my country.

934
01:11:20,966 --> 01:11:24,200
I am nowhere near as great as my country.

935
01:11:25,166 --> 01:11:28,400
And my strength lies not in my name,

936
01:11:29,633 --> 01:11:32,200
but in the backing of 1.4 billion Indians,

937
01:11:32,966 --> 01:11:35,966
and thousands of years of timeless culture
and heritage.

938
01:11:37,166 --> 01:11:41,533
So, wherever I go, I carry with me the
essence of

939
01:11:41,633 --> 01:11:47,400
thousands of years of Vedic tradition, the
timeless teachings of Swami Vivekananda,

940
01:11:48,133 --> 01:11:54,066
and the blessings, dreams, and aspirations
of 1.4 billion Indians.

941
01:11:55,533 --> 01:12:00,966
When I shake hands with a world leader,
it's not Modi,

942
01:12:01,066 --> 01:12:03,866
but 1.4 billion Indians
doing so.

943
01:12:04,766 --> 01:12:09,000
So, this isn't my strength at all. It is
rather the strength of India.

944
01:12:09,900 --> 01:12:14,266
You see, I recall something that
happened all the way back in 2013.

945
01:12:15,700 --> 01:12:19,900
It was when my party declared I would be
their Prime Ministerial candidate.

946
01:12:21,900 --> 01:12:24,900
My critics often tried to corner me on one
point.

947
01:12:25,866 --> 01:12:29,033
It became a topic of widespread
discussion.

948
01:12:29,633 --> 01:12:32,200
"Modi is nothing more than a
state leader."

949
01:12:33,000 --> 01:12:38,100
"What does he know of foreign policy? Does
he even understand global geopolitics?"

950
01:12:38,566 --> 01:12:40,600
This was on everyone's lips,

951
01:12:40,833 --> 01:12:46,066
and I was
asked this question in every interview.

952
01:12:46,800 --> 01:12:50,933
I gave a very well thought-out answer at
the time.

953
01:12:51,500 --> 01:12:56,266
I said, "I won’t lay out my entire foreign
policy in an interview, nor is it needed."

954
01:12:57,533 --> 01:13:01,800
That said, India will

955
01:13:02,633 --> 01:13:05,600
neither allow itself
to be looked down upon,

956
01:13:07,166 --> 01:13:09,900
nor will it ever
look up to anyone,

957
01:13:10,666 --> 01:13:15,166
India will now see eye-to-eye with her
counterparts.

958
01:13:16,233 --> 01:13:22,466
This was my belief in 2013, and it still
lies at the heart of my foreign policy.

959
01:13:22,966 --> 01:13:25,000
For me, the country always comes first.

960
01:13:25,600 --> 01:13:31,266
However, to belittle someone, or speaking
ill of others,

961
01:13:32,533 --> 01:13:37,066
is neither part of my
cultural values, nor my traditions.

962
01:13:38,833 --> 01:13:43,466
Moreover, our culture upholds and
advocates for the welfare of mankind.

963
01:13:45,100 --> 01:13:49,366
India has always championed the ideas of
global peace and brotherhood.

964
01:13:49,600 --> 01:13:52,900
For centuries, we have envisioned the
world as one big family.

965
01:13:53,366 --> 01:13:58,366
Our noble ancestors envisaged the welfare
of the whole world and universe.

966
01:13:59,766 --> 01:14:04,266
And that’s why you must have noticed, the
nature of our conversations

967
01:14:04,400 --> 01:14:08,533
as well as the ideas, that I have
presented on the global stage,

968
01:14:08,733 --> 01:14:11,266
which are
rooted in respect and positivity.

969
01:14:12,100 --> 01:14:16,666
For example, I spoke about the
environment in one of my speeches.

970
01:14:16,833 --> 01:14:22,066
I proposed the concept of One Sun, One
World, One Grid.

971
01:14:22,666 --> 01:14:27,966
During the COVID pandemic, I delivered a
speech at the G-20 Summit.

972
01:14:28,800 --> 01:14:31,600
I put forth the vision

973
01:14:37,566 --> 01:14:39,300
of One Health,

974
01:14:39,733 --> 01:14:42,266
where humans and nature would live in
harmony.

975
01:14:42,766 --> 01:14:45,700
And I have always worked towards this.

976
01:14:46,866 --> 01:14:52,700
We hosted the G-20 Summit with the motto,
"One Earth, One Family, One Future."

977
01:14:54,200 --> 01:14:56,533
We have inherited this
timeless wisdom,

978
01:14:56,600 --> 01:14:58,666
and it's our duty to
share it with the world.

979
01:14:58,966 --> 01:15:03,100
To give you an example, I have advocated
for embracing renewable energy.

980
01:15:04,300 --> 01:15:08,100
We founded the International Solar
Alliance with the motto,

981
01:15:08,133 --> 01:15:09,766
"One Sun, One
World, One Grid."

982
01:15:10,533 --> 01:15:15,966
Even when it comes to global healthcare, I
had proposed "One Earth, One Health".

983
01:15:16,900 --> 01:15:20,333
This initiative extends

984
01:15:20,633 --> 01:15:26,666
not only to humans
but also to all flora and fauna.

985
01:15:27,466 --> 01:15:29,866
I have always aimed to

986
01:15:30,433 --> 01:15:34,966
initiate efforts
that foster global well-being.

987
01:15:36,100 --> 01:15:39,366
And the global community needs to join
hands to accomplish that.

988
01:15:39,900 --> 01:15:44,066
We must also understand that the world has
become one small village today.

989
01:15:45,366 --> 01:15:47,700
No country can thrive in isolation.

990
01:15:48,566 --> 01:15:50,566
Today, we all depend upon one another.

991
01:15:51,366 --> 01:15:53,366
No one can make it far by themselves.

992
01:15:54,600 --> 01:15:59,400
That is why you must learn to synchronize
with everyone.

993
01:15:59,666 --> 01:16:02,966
And everyone else must learn to
synchronize with you.

994
01:16:03,200 --> 01:16:06,066
That's the only way to propel this
initiative forward.

995
01:16:06,566 --> 01:16:11,133
Organizations like the United Nations came
into being after the First World War,

996
01:16:12,166 --> 01:16:16,200
but they failed to evolve with the times.

997
01:16:16,700 --> 01:16:22,666
And this inability to adapt has sparked a
global debate on their relevance.

998
01:16:23,566 --> 01:16:25,600
- You have spoken about—

999
01:16:25,666 --> 01:16:30,300
You have the experience, you have the
skill, you have the geopolitical leverage

1000
01:16:30,766 --> 01:16:34,166
to be the biggest peacemaker in the world
today, on the world stage,

1001
01:16:34,200 --> 01:16:36,066
and there are several wars going on.

1002
01:16:37,466 --> 01:16:41,966
Can you, maybe, explain how you approach
the process of making peace,

1003
01:16:42,866 --> 01:16:46,500
helping make peace between two warring
nations?

1004
01:16:47,100 --> 01:16:49,466
For example, Russia and Ukraine.

1005
01:16:51,400 --> 01:16:56,266
- Well, I represent the country that is
the land

1006
01:16:57,166 --> 01:16:59,066
of Lord Buddha.

1007
01:17:00,566 --> 01:17:03,566
I represent the country that is

1008
01:17:04,033 --> 01:17:06,166
the land
of Mahatma Gandhi.

1009
01:17:06,900 --> 01:17:13,466
These are the great souls whose teachings,
words, actions, and behavior

1010
01:17:13,700 --> 01:17:16,900
are entirely
dedicated to peace.

1011
01:17:17,566 --> 01:17:19,033
And that is why,

1012
01:17:20,233 --> 01:17:25,866
culturally and
historically, our background is so strong

1013
01:17:26,666 --> 01:17:32,266
that whenever we speak of peace, the world
listens to us.

1014
01:17:33,333 --> 01:17:39,300
Because India is the land of Gautama
Buddha and Mahatma Gandhi.

1015
01:17:39,900 --> 01:17:44,500
And Indians aren't hardwired to espouse
strife and conflict.

1016
01:17:45,866 --> 01:17:48,066
We espouse harmony instead.

1017
01:17:48,666 --> 01:17:51,866
We seek neither to wage war against
nature,

1018
01:17:51,900 --> 01:17:54,466
nor to foster strife among
nations.

1019
01:17:54,866 --> 01:17:56,866
We stand for peace.

1020
01:17:57,100 --> 01:18:02,900
And wherever we can act as peacemakers, we
have gladly embraced that responsibility.

1021
01:18:03,166 --> 01:18:05,800
Returning to your example,

1022
01:18:06,766 --> 01:18:10,633
I have a close relationship with
Russia and Ukraine alike.

1023
01:18:13,133 --> 01:18:18,766
I can sit with President Putin, and say
that this is not the time for war

1024
01:18:19,500 --> 01:18:22,866
And I can also tell President Zelensky, in
a friendly way,

1025
01:18:23,800 --> 01:18:28,766
that brother, regardless of how many
people stand with you in the world,

1026
01:18:31,366 --> 01:18:35,266
there will never be a resolution on the
battlefield.

1027
01:18:36,066 --> 01:18:38,566
The resolution will only come

1028
01:18:39,866 --> 01:18:46,566
when both Ukraine and Russia
come to the negotiating table.

1029
01:18:46,666 --> 01:18:52,466
Ukraine may hold countless discussions
with their allies, but it will bear no fruit.

1030
01:18:52,700 --> 01:18:55,666
Discussions must include
both parties instead.

1031
01:18:56,300 --> 01:19:01,500
Initially, it was challenging to find
peace, but now,

1032
01:19:02,566 --> 01:19:06,066
the current situation presents an
opportunity

1033
01:19:06,400 --> 01:19:11,000
for meaningful and productive
talks between Ukraine and Russia.

1034
01:19:12,000 --> 01:19:16,966
There has been a lot of suffering. Even
the Global South has suffered.

1035
01:19:17,466 --> 01:19:20,966
The world has been grappling with a food,
fuel, and fertilizer crisis.

1036
01:19:21,766 --> 01:19:25,466
So, the global community should unite in
the pursuit of peace.

1037
01:19:27,166 --> 01:19:30,533
As for me, I have always maintained that I
stand with peace.

1038
01:19:31,366 --> 01:19:34,400
I am not neutral. I have a stance, and
that is peace.

1039
01:19:34,600 --> 01:19:36,166
And peace is what I strive
for.

1040
01:19:37,733 --> 01:19:43,166
- Another difficult, historic relationship
and conflict

1041
01:19:43,166 --> 01:19:45,666
is between India and
Pakistan.

1042
01:19:46,566 --> 01:19:49,266
So, it's one of the most tense conflicts
in the world.

1043
01:19:49,766 --> 01:19:53,466
Two nuclear powers with strong ideological
differences.

1044
01:19:54,366 --> 01:20:00,200
You are a great peacemaker. Looking out
into the future as a visionary,

1045
01:20:00,766 --> 01:20:04,366
what do you see is the path for
friendship, for peace,

1046
01:20:04,366 --> 01:20:06,766
for good relations
between India and Pakistan?

1047
01:20:09,166 --> 01:20:14,700
- I would like to delve into periods of
our history

1048
01:20:15,000 --> 01:20:17,266
the world may be unfamiliar
with.

1049
01:20:19,300 --> 01:20:23,033
Before 1947, during the struggle for
independence,

1050
01:20:24,266 --> 01:20:28,400
everyone was fighting side
by side, shoulder to shoulder.

1051
01:20:37,066 --> 01:20:40,566
And the nation was eagerly waiting to
celebrate the freedom,

1052
01:20:40,700 --> 01:20:42,500
the joy of
independence.

1053
01:20:44,133 --> 01:20:49,833
Now, we could have a lengthy discussion on

1054
01:20:50,500 --> 01:20:53,200
what led to the events that unfolded.

1055
01:20:55,900 --> 01:21:00,466
But the fact remains that the policymakers
of the time agreed to India's partition.

1056
01:21:02,466 --> 01:21:06,900
And they agreed to the Muslim side's
demand of carving out a separate nation.

1057
01:21:07,200 --> 01:21:11,866
With hearts weighed down by grief and
silent tears,

1058
01:21:13,633 --> 01:21:18,566
Indians embraced this
painful reality.

1059
01:21:19,366 --> 01:21:26,366
However, what unfolded was an immediate,
heartbreaking saga of bloodshed.

1060
01:21:28,066 --> 01:21:31,400
Trains filled with bloodied,
wounded people  and corpses

1061
01:21:31,433 --> 01:21:34,000
started arriving from Pakistan.

1062
01:21:34,166 --> 01:21:36,266
It was a harrowing sight.

1063
01:21:39,200 --> 01:21:45,766
After getting their own way, we expected
them to live and let live.

1064
01:21:46,100 --> 01:21:50,300
And yet, they chose not to foster a
harmonious coexistence.

1065
01:21:50,500 --> 01:21:53,666
Time and again they decided to be at odds
with India.

1066
01:21:54,233 --> 01:21:56,466
They have waged a proxy war against us.

1067
01:21:57,566 --> 01:21:59,866
Don't mistake this for ideology.

1068
01:22:01,000 --> 01:22:05,300
What kind of ideology thrives on bloodshed
and the export of terror?

1069
01:22:05,366 --> 01:22:08,700
And we are not the sole victims of this
menace.

1070
01:22:10,066 --> 01:22:13,066
Wherever terror strikes in the world,

1071
01:22:13,500 --> 01:22:18,666
the trail somehow
leads to Pakistan.

1072
01:22:19,100 --> 01:22:22,700
Let's take the September 11 attacks for
example.

1073
01:22:24,300 --> 01:22:27,233
The main mastermind behind it,
Osama Bin Laden,

1074
01:22:27,666 --> 01:22:29,600
where did he eventually emerge
from?

1075
01:22:30,200 --> 01:22:32,266
He had taken refuge in Pakistan.

1076
01:22:32,900 --> 01:22:35,000
The world has recognized that,

1077
01:22:35,966 --> 01:22:39,766
in a way, terrorism and
the terrorist mindset are

1078
01:22:39,866 --> 01:22:41,900
deeply rooted in Pakistan.

1079
01:22:42,300 --> 01:22:48,766
Today, it stands as an epicenter of turmoil,
not just for India, but for the world.

1080
01:22:49,333 --> 01:22:54,266
And we have repeatedly asked them what
good can come from this path?

1081
01:22:54,833 --> 01:23:01,466
We have urged them to abandon the path of
state-sponsored terrorism for good.

1082
01:23:01,833 --> 01:23:05,566
What do you hope to gain by surrendering
your nation to lawless forces?

1083
01:23:05,766 --> 01:23:09,633
I've even personally traveled to Lahore in
the pursuit of peace.

1084
01:23:11,333 --> 01:23:18,000
When I became Prime Minister, I specially
invited Pakistan to my swearing-in ceremony

1085
01:23:18,433 --> 01:23:20,400
so we could turn over a new leaf.

1086
01:23:21,333 --> 01:23:26,566
Yet, every noble attempt at fostering
peace was met with hostility and betrayal.

1087
01:23:27,566 --> 01:23:31,566
We sincerely hope that wisdom prevails
upon them

1088
01:23:32,333 --> 01:23:34,400
and they choose the path of peace.

1089
01:23:34,900 --> 01:23:38,266
I believe even the people of Pakistan long
for peace.

1090
01:23:39,100 --> 01:23:42,966
Because even they must be weary of living
in strife and unrest.

1091
01:23:43,466 --> 01:23:47,100
They must have grown weary of relentless
terror,

1092
01:23:47,300 --> 01:23:50,066
where even innocent children are
killed

1093
01:23:50,300 --> 01:23:53,100
and countless lives are destroyed.

1094
01:23:54,066 --> 01:24:00,166
- Are there any memorable stories from
your past attempts

1095
01:24:01,066 --> 01:24:05,000
to try to improve relations with Pakistan
that could

1096
01:24:05,300 --> 01:24:08,566
guide the path forward into the
future?

1097
01:24:09,466 --> 01:24:13,800
- Like I mentioned, my first attempt at
improving bilateral relations was

1098
01:24:16,033 --> 01:24:20,700
when I invited my Pakistani counterpart to
my swearing-in.

1099
01:24:21,666 --> 01:24:24,066
It was a gesture of
goodwill.

1100
01:24:24,433 --> 01:24:28,100
It was a diplomatic gesture unlike any in
decades.

1101
01:24:28,400 --> 01:24:33,966
The very people who once questioned my
approach to foreign policy

1102
01:24:34,566 --> 01:24:37,600
were taken aback when they learned

1103
01:24:37,966 --> 01:24:41,966
I had invited all
SAARC heads of state.

1104
01:24:42,800 --> 01:24:49,600
And our then President, Mr. Pranab
Mukherjee,

1105
01:24:50,733 --> 01:24:56,266
beautifully captured that historic gesture
in his memoir.

1106
01:24:56,900 --> 01:25:02,033
This was a testament to how clear and
confident

1107
01:25:02,233 --> 01:25:05,766
India's foreign policy had become.

1108
01:25:06,366 --> 01:25:09,100
This sent a clear message to the world

1109
01:25:09,300 --> 01:25:12,600
about India's commitment to
peace and harmony.

1110
01:25:13,700 --> 01:25:15,866
But we didn't get the desired outcome.

1111
01:25:16,366 --> 01:25:19,500
- Maybe to ask a little bit of a lighter
question,

1112
01:25:19,566 --> 01:25:22,966
who has the better cricket team, India or
Pakistan?

1113
01:25:23,666 --> 01:25:27,366
The two teams have a epic rivalry on the
pitch

1114
01:25:27,866 --> 01:25:32,466
and more seriously given the geopolitical
tensions that you spoke to,

1115
01:25:34,066 --> 01:25:36,800
what role do sports and cricket

1116
01:25:37,766 --> 01:25:43,066
and football play in fostering better
relations?

1117
01:25:44,866 --> 01:25:47,833
- I think sports have

1118
01:25:48,666 --> 01:25:53,266
the power to
energize the entire world.

1119
01:25:53,966 --> 01:25:59,166
The spirit of sports brings people
together across different nations.

1120
01:25:59,966 --> 01:26:02,966
That’s why I would never want to see
sports being discredited.

1121
01:26:04,866 --> 01:26:10,566
I truly believe that sports play a major
role in human evolution,

1122
01:26:10,766 --> 01:26:15,200
they’re not just games; they connect
people on a deeper level.

1123
01:26:16,266 --> 01:26:19,500
Now, coming to the question of who’s
better and who’s not.

1124
01:26:21,266 --> 01:26:27,366
When it comes to techniques in sports,
I’m not an expert.

1125
01:26:27,766 --> 01:26:31,366
Only those who specialize in the technical
aspects can judge

1126
01:26:31,566 --> 01:26:34,666
which techniques are superior and who the
best players really are.

1127
01:26:35,066 --> 01:26:39,200
But sometimes, the results speak for
themselves.

1128
01:26:39,733 --> 01:26:43,900
Just a few days ago, India and Pakistan
played a match.

1129
01:26:44,633 --> 01:26:50,333
The result reveals which is the better
team. That’s how we know.

1130
01:26:51,133 --> 01:26:54,300
- Yeah, I've, I've watched the series
called the greatest rivalry,

1131
01:26:54,333 --> 01:26:58,933
India vs. Pakistan, that describes so many
incredible players, so many incredible games.

1132
01:26:58,933 --> 01:27:02,433
It's, it's always beautiful to see a great
rivalry.

1133
01:27:02,833 --> 01:27:07,833
You've also spoken about football.
Football is very popular in India.

1134
01:27:08,033 --> 01:27:12,133
So another tough question, who is the
greatest football player of all time?

1135
01:27:12,366 --> 01:27:16,733
We've got Messi, Pelé, Maradona,
Cristiano Ronaldo, Zidane.

1136
01:27:16,766 --> 01:27:21,633
Who do you think is the greatest football
player to have ever played?

1137
01:27:22,466 --> 01:27:27,766
- It’s absolutely true that many regions
in India have a strong football culture.

1138
01:27:27,833 --> 01:27:31,533
Our women’s football team is performing
really well,

1139
01:27:31,833 --> 01:27:34,600
and the men’s team is also making great
progress.

1140
01:27:35,066 --> 01:27:39,433
But if we talk about the past, back in the
1980s,

1141
01:27:40,233 --> 01:27:43,666
one name that always stood out was
Maradona.

1142
01:27:44,333 --> 01:27:49,633
For that generation, he was seen
as a true hero.

1143
01:27:50,366 --> 01:27:54,166
And if you ask today’s generation, they’ll
immediately mention Messi.

1144
01:27:54,866 --> 01:27:59,533
Now that you’ve asked, another interesting
memory just came to mind.

1145
01:28:00,366 --> 01:28:05,933
There’s a state in India called Madhya
Pradesh, right in the center.

1146
01:28:06,566 --> 01:28:09,366
There’s a district called Shahdol,

1147
01:28:09,700 --> 01:28:13,900
a completely tribal region where a large
tribal community resides.

1148
01:28:14,333 --> 01:28:18,133
I really enjoy interacting with people
from such communities,

1149
01:28:18,733 --> 01:28:23,133
especially the self-help groups run by
tribal women.

1150
01:28:23,133 --> 01:28:25,466
So, I decided to visit them and have a
conversation.

1151
01:28:26,033 --> 01:28:31,033
But when I got there, I noticed something
fascinating, around 80 to 100 young boys,

1152
01:28:31,766 --> 01:28:35,033
kids, and even some
older youth,

1153
01:28:35,233 --> 01:28:38,466
all dressed in sports uniforms,
standing together.

1154
01:28:38,633 --> 01:28:40,466
Naturally, I walked over to them.

1155
01:28:41,033 --> 01:28:43,466
So, I asked them,
"Where are you all from?"

1156
01:28:43,666 --> 01:28:45,866
And they replied,
"We’re from Mini Brazil!"

1157
01:28:46,800 --> 01:28:49,633
I was surprised and said,
"What do you mean by Mini Brazil?"

1158
01:28:49,933 --> 01:28:52,500
They said,
"That’s what people call our village."

1159
01:28:52,866 --> 01:28:55,466
Curious, I asked,
"Why do they call it Mini Brazil?"

1160
01:28:55,833 --> 01:28:57,166
They explained,

1161
01:28:58,433 --> 01:29:02,933
"In our village, football
has been played for four generations.

1162
01:29:04,066 --> 01:29:08,366
Nearly 80 national-level players have come
from here.

1163
01:29:08,966 --> 01:29:11,600
Our entire village is dedicated to
football.

1164
01:29:11,700 --> 01:29:14,966
They also told me, "When we host our
annual football match,

1165
01:29:15,100 --> 01:29:20,233
nearly 20 to 25 thousand spectators come
from nearby villages to watch.

1166
01:29:20,533 --> 01:29:26,733
I see the growing craze for football in
India these days as a positive sign

1167
01:29:26,900 --> 01:29:31,533
because it not only fuels passion, but
also builds true team spirit.

1168
01:29:31,866 --> 01:29:36,066
- Yeah, football is one of the great
sports that unites not just India,

1169
01:29:36,133 --> 01:29:40,966
the whole world, and that, that just shows
the power of what sport can do.

1170
01:29:41,733 --> 01:29:44,433
You recently visited the United States

1171
01:29:45,233 --> 01:29:49,733
and, reinvigorated your friendship with
Donald Trump.

1172
01:29:50,433 --> 01:29:53,933
What do you like about Donald Trump as a
friend, as a leader?

1173
01:29:54,933 --> 01:29:58,433
- I'd like to share with you an event that
stands out in my memory.

1174
01:29:58,833 --> 01:30:03,833
Perhaps from that, you'll get a better
understanding of the point

1175
01:30:03,866 --> 01:30:05,033
I'm trying to convey.

1176
01:30:05,633 --> 01:30:09,933
For example, we had an event
in Houston, Howdy Modi.

1177
01:30:11,233 --> 01:30:16,433
Both President Trump and I were there, and
the entire stadium was completely packed.

1178
01:30:17,200 --> 01:30:20,433
A massive crowd at an event in the U.S. is
a huge moment.

1179
01:30:20,933 --> 01:30:23,433
While packed stadiums are common in
sports,

1180
01:30:23,433 --> 01:30:25,833
this was extraordinary for a political
rally.

1181
01:30:26,266 --> 01:30:28,966
The Indian diaspora had gathered in large
numbers.

1182
01:30:30,933 --> 01:30:35,733
Both of us delivered speeches, and he sat
down below, listening to me speak.

1183
01:30:36,466 --> 01:30:38,233
Now, that’s his humility.

1184
01:30:38,600 --> 01:30:41,366
The President of the United States sitting
in the audience,

1185
01:30:41,400 --> 01:30:46,133
while I spoke from the stage that was a
remarkable gesture on his part.

1186
01:30:46,366 --> 01:30:48,733
After finishing my speech, I stepped down.

1187
01:30:49,633 --> 01:30:55,566
And as we all know, security in the U.S.
is extremely strict and thorough

1188
01:30:56,166 --> 01:30:59,433
The level of scrutiny there is on a
completely different level.

1189
01:31:00,233 --> 01:31:04,766
I went over to thank him,
and casually said,

1190
01:31:05,166 --> 01:31:11,466
"If you don’t mind, why don’t we take a
lap around the stadium?

1191
01:31:11,533 --> 01:31:14,766
There are so many people here, let’s walk,
wave, and greet them."

1192
01:31:15,900 --> 01:31:18,766
In American life, it’s almost impossible

1193
01:31:19,233 --> 01:31:22,566
for the President to walk into a crowd of
thousands.

1194
01:31:23,566 --> 01:31:30,166
But without even a moment’s hesitation, he
agreed and started walking with me.

1195
01:31:30,966 --> 01:31:34,833
His entire security detail
was thrown off guard.

1196
01:31:35,366 --> 01:31:38,733
But for me, that moment was truly
touching,

1197
01:31:38,933 --> 01:31:41,266
it showed me that this man had
courage.

1198
01:31:42,633 --> 01:31:48,566
He makes his own decisions, but also, he
trusted me and my lead in that moment

1199
01:31:48,600 --> 01:31:51,533
enough to have walked
with me into the crowd.

1200
01:31:53,133 --> 01:31:58,400
It was that sense of mutual trust, a
strong bond between us,

1201
01:31:58,433 --> 01:32:01,033
that I truly
witnessed on that day.

1202
01:32:01,233 --> 01:32:05,466
And the way I saw President Trump that
day, walking into a

1203
01:32:07,566 --> 01:32:11,666
crowd of thousands without
even asking security was truly amazing.

1204
01:32:12,200 --> 01:32:15,366
And if you watch the video now,
you’ll be amazed.

1205
01:32:15,466 --> 01:32:19,000
When he was shot during the recent
campaign,

1206
01:32:19,266 --> 01:32:24,733
I saw the same resilient and
determined President Trump.

1207
01:32:26,033 --> 01:32:29,766
The one who walked hand in hand with me in
that stadium.

1208
01:32:30,533 --> 01:32:35,633
Even after being shot, he remained
unwaveringly dedicated to America,

1209
01:32:36,533 --> 01:32:38,733
his life was for his nation.

1210
01:32:39,266 --> 01:32:43,266
His reflection showed his,
'America First spirit', just as

1211
01:32:43,733 --> 01:32:46,133
I believe in Nation First.

1212
01:32:46,466 --> 01:32:50,333
I stand for India First and that’s why we
connect so well.

1213
01:32:51,166 --> 01:32:56,100
These are the things that truly resonate.

1214
01:32:56,433 --> 01:33:01,166
And I believe that, across the world,

1215
01:33:01,433 --> 01:33:04,433
politicians are covered so
much by the media

1216
01:33:04,766 --> 01:33:08,266
that people mostly perceive each other
through its lens.

1217
01:33:10,266 --> 01:33:14,933
People rarely get the chance to truly meet
or personally know one another.

1218
01:33:15,166 --> 01:33:19,266
And perhaps, third-party intervention is
the real cause of tensions.

1219
01:33:19,533 --> 01:33:22,933
When I visited him in the White House for
the first time,

1220
01:33:26,466 --> 01:33:30,833
there was already a lot written about
President Trump in the media.

1221
01:33:30,900 --> 01:33:32,733
At that time, he was still new to office,

1222
01:33:32,733 --> 01:33:36,566
and the world had a rather different
perception of him.

1223
01:33:37,400 --> 01:33:40,633
Even I had been briefed in many different
ways before meeting him.

1224
01:33:41,566 --> 01:33:45,466
But to my surprise, the very moment I
stepped into the White House,

1225
01:33:46,333 --> 01:33:49,433
he broke all formal protocols right away.

1226
01:33:50,166 --> 01:33:53,866
And then, he personally took me on a tour
of the White House.

1227
01:33:54,233 --> 01:33:57,200
As he showed me around,
I noticed something striking,

1228
01:33:57,233 --> 01:33:58,666
he wasn’t holding
any notes,

1229
01:33:58,900 --> 01:34:03,033
or cue cards, nor was anyone
accompanying him to assist.

1230
01:34:03,300 --> 01:34:07,566
He pointed things out himself. "This is
where Abraham Lincoln lived," he said.

1231
01:34:07,600 --> 01:34:11,100
He even explained why the courtroom was
designed so long.

1232
01:34:11,133 --> 01:34:12,733
He would point at the table and tell me
which

1233
01:34:12,733 --> 01:34:15,033
President signed here and on what date.

1234
01:34:15,266 --> 01:34:17,933
I found that incredibly impressive,

1235
01:34:19,133 --> 01:34:22,233
it showed how much he
honored the Presidency,

1236
01:34:23,933 --> 01:34:29,566
And, how respectful and deeply connected
he was to America’s history.

1237
01:34:29,833 --> 01:34:35,433
I could feel that. And he spoke to me
freely, discussing many things openly.

1238
01:34:35,633 --> 01:34:38,233
That was my experience from our first
meeting.

1239
01:34:39,333 --> 01:34:44,033
Later, when his first term ended

1240
01:34:44,866 --> 01:34:50,333
and President Biden won,
four years passed.

1241
01:34:52,833 --> 01:34:56,433
But during that time, whenever someone we
both knew met him,

1242
01:34:57,733 --> 01:35:00,666
and this must have happened dozens of
times,

1243
01:35:02,066 --> 01:35:06,333
he would say, "Modi is my friend, convey
my regards."

1244
01:35:07,633 --> 01:35:09,733
That kind of gesture is rare.

1245
01:35:10,933 --> 01:35:13,866
Even though we didn’t meet
physically for years,

1246
01:35:14,600 --> 01:35:17,233
our direct and
indirect communication,

1247
01:35:18,133 --> 01:35:22,266
our closeness, and the trust between us
remained unshaken.

1248
01:35:22,566 --> 01:35:28,466
- He said that you're a much, tougher,
much better negotiator than he is.

1249
01:35:28,533 --> 01:35:30,333
He said this recently when you visited.

1250
01:35:32,033 --> 01:35:34,233
What do you think of him as a negotiator

1251
01:35:34,433 --> 01:35:38,733
and what do you think he meant about, you
being a great negotiator?

1252
01:35:39,333 --> 01:35:41,566
- Now, that’s not something I can comment
on,

1253
01:35:41,633 --> 01:35:43,866
since it's his graciousness and humility.

1254
01:35:45,433 --> 01:35:49,033
It is very kind of him that

1255
01:35:49,333 --> 01:35:54,033
he openly appreciates me on various
occasions, and in different contexts.

1256
01:35:54,333 --> 01:36:00,033
But about negotiation, I always put my
country’s interests first.

1257
01:36:00,533 --> 01:36:05,266
That’s why, in every forum, I speak up for
India’s interests,

1258
01:36:06,366 --> 01:36:08,433
not to harm anyone,

1259
01:36:09,033 --> 01:36:13,866
but in a positive manner. And because of
that, no one takes offense.

1260
01:36:15,233 --> 01:36:20,400
People know that if Modi is present, he
will strongly advocate for these things.

1261
01:36:20,600 --> 01:36:24,133
After all, the people of India have given
me this responsibility.

1262
01:36:24,666 --> 01:36:27,266
For me, my nation is my High Command,

1263
01:36:27,833 --> 01:36:29,733
and I will always honor their will.

1264
01:36:30,433 --> 01:36:32,933
- You've also had a bunch of productive
meetings with

1265
01:36:32,966 --> 01:36:35,466
several other folks on your visit to the
United States,

1266
01:36:35,533 --> 01:36:39,233
Elon Musk, JD Vance, Tulsi Gabbard, Vivek
Ramaswamy.

1267
01:36:39,666 --> 01:36:43,533
What are some things that stood out from
those meetings?

1268
01:36:43,933 --> 01:36:46,333
Maybe key takeaways, key memories.

1269
01:36:46,766 --> 01:36:52,633
- Look, I can say this, I have observed
President Trump both during his first term

1270
01:36:52,933 --> 01:36:54,633
and now in his second run.

1271
01:36:55,533 --> 01:36:58,666
This time, he seems far more
prepared than before.

1272
01:37:00,266 --> 01:37:02,633
He has a clear roadmap in his mind,

1273
01:37:03,233 --> 01:37:08,333
with well-defined steps, each one designed
to lead him toward his goals.

1274
01:37:09,233 --> 01:37:11,866
I also had the chance to meet members of
his team,

1275
01:37:11,966 --> 01:37:16,933
and I truly believe he has put together a
strong, capable group.

1276
01:37:18,133 --> 01:37:22,233
And with such a strong team, I feel they
are fully capable

1277
01:37:23,100 --> 01:37:29,466
of implementing President Trump’s vision,
based on my interactions with them.

1278
01:37:30,533 --> 01:37:37,333
I met several people: Tulsi Gabbard, Vivek
Ramaswamy, Elon Musk,

1279
01:37:38,966 --> 01:37:43,066
and there was a family-like atmosphere.
Everyone had come with their families.

1280
01:37:44,366 --> 01:37:49,233
As for Elon Musk, I’ve known him since my
time as Chief Minister.

1281
01:37:49,666 --> 01:37:51,633
He was there with his family and children,

1282
01:37:51,666 --> 01:37:54,833
so naturally, the atmosphere
felt warm and friendly.

1283
01:37:55,266 --> 01:37:58,933
Of course, we had discussions and we
talked about many different topics.

1284
01:37:59,266 --> 01:38:03,433
Now, with his Doge mission, he is
incredibly excited about

1285
01:38:04,000 --> 01:38:05,666
how it's
progressing.

1286
01:38:06,233 --> 01:38:11,966
And honestly, it makes me happy too,
because when I took office in 2014,

1287
01:38:12,833 --> 01:38:15,966
I wanted to free my country from the
deep-rooted issues

1288
01:38:16,433 --> 01:38:18,933
and harmful practices
that have crept in,

1289
01:38:19,966 --> 01:38:25,933
and I'll continue striving to eliminate as
many of them as I possibly can.

1290
01:38:26,333 --> 01:38:31,466
For example, after I took office in 2014,
I observed that

1291
01:38:31,833 --> 01:38:35,533
back then, we weren’t part of many global
discussions,

1292
01:38:35,633 --> 01:38:39,133
not like how President Trump and Doge are
being talked about today.

1293
01:38:39,166 --> 01:38:43,066
But let me give you an example so you can
see the kind of work that was done.

1294
01:38:43,233 --> 01:38:48,766
I noticed that the benefits of certain
government schemes,

1295
01:38:50,033 --> 01:38:52,266
especially welfare programs,

1296
01:38:56,133 --> 01:38:59,166
were being exploited by so many people

1297
01:39:00,033 --> 01:39:02,333
who
never even existed in real life.

1298
01:39:04,133 --> 01:39:08,233
There were ghost names, pensions being
issued to fake people,

1299
01:39:08,266 --> 01:39:12,100
widow pensions were being granted even
before marriages took place,

1300
01:39:12,200 --> 01:39:16,633
and disability pensions were given without
any real disabilities.

1301
01:39:17,100 --> 01:39:21,900
Then, I launched a scrutiny process and
you’ll be shocked to know what we found.

1302
01:39:23,466 --> 01:39:25,900
A hundred million people.

1303
01:39:27,033 --> 01:39:29,133
A hundred million people.

1304
01:39:30,233 --> 01:39:36,233
That’s 100 million fake or duplicate names
that I removed from the system.

1305
01:39:37,233 --> 01:39:38,533
And because of that,

1306
01:39:38,533 --> 01:39:40,333
We saved massive amount of money.

1307
01:39:40,533 --> 01:39:42,833
Then I introduced
Direct Benefit Transfer,

1308
01:39:43,033 --> 01:39:47,366
ensuring that every rupee sent from Delhi
reached the rightful person without leakage.

1309
01:39:48,133 --> 01:39:52,600
As a result, my country
saved nearly ₹3 trillion

1310
01:39:52,766 --> 01:39:56,000
that would have otherwise ended
up in the wrong hands.

1311
01:39:56,133 --> 01:39:59,333
Just because of Direct Benefit Transfer
through technology,

1312
01:39:59,500 --> 01:40:01,033
we eliminated
middlemen,

1313
01:40:01,200 --> 01:40:03,300
ensuring transparency in the
system.

1314
01:40:03,566 --> 01:40:07,933
I also introduced the GEM Portal for
government purchases,

1315
01:40:08,433 --> 01:40:11,366
which has helped save both time and money.

1316
01:40:11,933 --> 01:40:15,033
It has increased competition
and improved quality.

1317
01:40:15,600 --> 01:40:18,700
In India, we had an overwhelming
burden of compliances.

1318
01:40:19,133 --> 01:40:22,133
I eliminated 40,000 unnecessary
compliances

1319
01:40:22,666 --> 01:40:28,866
and removed nearly 1,500 outdated laws
that served no purpose.

1320
01:40:29,533 --> 01:40:34,666
So, in a way, my efforts have been about
freeing governance

1321
01:40:36,133 --> 01:40:40,933
from unnecessary dominance and
inefficiency.

1322
01:40:40,966 --> 01:40:46,266
And naturally, when bold changes happen,
just like Doge’s mission,

1323
01:40:46,433 --> 01:40:49,833
they become a topic of discussion
worldwide.

1324
01:40:50,233 --> 01:40:55,166
- You have, you and Xi Jinping have
considered each other friends.

1325
01:40:55,366 --> 01:40:58,533
How can that friendship
be reinvigorated

1326
01:40:58,533 --> 01:41:01,133
to help deescalate some of the recent
tensions and

1327
01:41:01,433 --> 01:41:04,533
resume dialogue and
cooperation with China?

1328
01:41:05,866 --> 01:41:07,133
- Look,

1329
01:41:10,133 --> 01:41:16,633
the relationship between
India and China

1330
01:41:16,766 --> 01:41:18,033
isn’t something new.

1331
01:41:20,466 --> 01:41:26,966
Both nations have ancient cultures and
civilizations.

1332
01:41:29,633 --> 01:41:34,066
Even in the modern world, they play a
significant role.

1333
01:41:36,633 --> 01:41:38,466
If you look at historical records,

1334
01:41:39,833 --> 01:41:45,633
for centuries, India and China have
learned from each other.

1335
01:41:46,366 --> 01:41:49,033
Together, they have always

1336
01:41:49,233 --> 01:41:53,433
contributed to
the global good in some way.

1337
01:41:53,633 --> 01:41:57,833
Old records suggest that at one point,
India and China

1338
01:41:57,966 --> 01:42:01,966
alone accounted for more than 50% of the
world’s GDP.

1339
01:42:02,533 --> 01:42:05,733
That’s how massive India’s contribution
was.

1340
01:42:06,533 --> 01:42:12,400
And I believe our ties have been extremely
strong,

1341
01:42:12,866 --> 01:42:15,066
with deep cultural connections.

1342
01:42:15,533 --> 01:42:19,666
If we look back centuries, there’s no real
history of conflict between us.

1343
01:42:20,533 --> 01:42:25,866
It has always been about learning from
each other and understanding one another.

1344
01:42:26,533 --> 01:42:30,333
At one time, Buddhism had a profound
influence in China,

1345
01:42:32,166 --> 01:42:35,333
and that philosophy originally came from
here.

1346
01:42:40,100 --> 01:42:45,933
Our relationship should remain just as
strong in the future.

1347
01:42:45,933 --> 01:42:47,233
It should continue to grow.

1348
01:42:48,133 --> 01:42:54,333
Of course, differences are natural, when
two neighboring countries exist,

1349
01:42:56,433 --> 01:42:59,466
occasional disagreements are bound to
happen.

1350
01:42:59,533 --> 01:43:02,733
Even within a family, not everything is
always perfect.

1351
01:43:03,966 --> 01:43:08,966
But our focus is to ensure that these
differences don’t turn into disputes.

1352
01:43:09,166 --> 01:43:11,533
That’s what we actively work toward.

1353
01:43:12,133 --> 01:43:14,033
Instead of discord,

1354
01:43:14,933 --> 01:43:20,433
we emphasize dialogue,

1355
01:43:20,566 --> 01:43:23,533
because only through dialogue

1356
01:43:23,733 --> 01:43:28,333
can we build
a stable, cooperative relationship

1357
01:43:29,566 --> 01:43:33,733
that serves the best interests of both
nations.

1358
01:43:35,433 --> 01:43:39,700
It is true that there have been ongoing
border disputes between us.

1359
01:43:40,700 --> 01:43:44,166
And in 2020, the incidents along the
border

1360
01:43:44,400 --> 01:43:48,466
created significant tensions between our
countries.

1361
01:43:48,833 --> 01:43:51,933
However, after my recent meeting with
President Xi,

1362
01:43:52,366 --> 01:43:55,433
