02:35:58,800 --> 02:36:05,200
And that real intelligence exists
abundantly in India's youth and talent pool.

2038
02:36:06,400 --> 02:36:10,100
And, I believe that's our greatest asset.

2039
02:36:10,700 --> 02:36:13,500
- But also, if you look, many of the top
tech leaders,

2040
02:36:14,100 --> 02:36:18,033
first of all, tech talent, but tech
leaders in the US are of Indian origin,

2041
02:36:18,300 --> 02:36:22,300
Sundar Pichai, Satya Nadella, Aravind
Srinivas,

2042
02:36:22,933 --> 02:36:28,766
you've met with some of them, what spirit

2043
02:36:28,800 --> 02:36:31,100
of their Indian origins do you think they
carry

2044
02:36:31,100 --> 02:36:33,800
in them that enables them to be so
successful?

2045
02:36:34,900 --> 02:36:38,333
- Look, Indian culture emphasizes that

2046
02:36:38,533 --> 02:36:42,100
there should be equal respect for the
place where you're born

2047
02:36:43,300 --> 02:36:48,433
and the place where you work.
There should be no difference.

2048
02:36:49,200 --> 02:36:52,233
As much as there is dedication
to the land of birth,

2049
02:36:52,266 --> 02:36:55,433
there should be the same sense of
dedication to the land of work.

2050
02:36:55,466 --> 02:36:58,300
You should always give your best,
wherever you are.

2051
02:36:58,500 --> 02:37:01,200
Because of these rich cultural values,

2052
02:37:01,333 --> 02:37:04,200
every Indian strives to
give their best effort,

2053
02:37:04,233 --> 02:37:06,600
regardless of their role or
position.

2054
02:37:06,633 --> 02:37:10,600
They don’t wait until they're in senior
roles; even in smaller roles,

2055
02:37:10,600 --> 02:37:14,500
Secondly, they never get involved in
anything questionable or unethical.

2056
02:37:14,633 --> 02:37:17,666
They tend to remain dedicated to what's
right and ethical.

2057
02:37:17,800 --> 02:37:21,033
Their nature is collaborative, they easily
get along with others.

2058
02:37:21,200 --> 02:37:25,733
Eventually, for success, just having
knowledge isn’t enough.

2059
02:37:26,466 --> 02:37:32,300
The ability to work effectively as part of
a team matters significantly more.

2060
02:37:32,433 --> 02:37:37,200
Understanding people and harnessing their
abilities is an incredibly valuable skill.

2061
02:37:38,400 --> 02:37:42,933
Generally, people raised in India,
especially those coming

2062
02:37:42,966 --> 02:37:46,000
from joint families and brought up in an
open society,

2063
02:37:46,400 --> 02:37:50,600
find it easier to lead complex tasks and
large teams effectively.

2064
02:37:50,933 --> 02:37:56,933
That's why today, in major corporations
across the globe,

2065
02:37:57,400 --> 02:38:00,900
you'll find Indians holding
key leadership positions.

2066
02:38:01,633 --> 02:38:06,400
And the problem-solving abilities, along
with the analytical thinking,

2067
02:38:06,633 --> 02:38:10,300
of Indian professionals,
are truly exceptional.

2068
02:38:11,933 --> 02:38:18,366
I believe this capability is so strong it
makes Indians globally competitive

2069
02:38:18,700 --> 02:38:23,733
and extremely valuable on the
international stage.

2070
02:38:24,500 --> 02:38:27,100
This is the reason why,

2071
02:38:27,933 --> 02:38:32,466
in fields like innovation, entrepreneurship,
startups, and boardrooms,

2072
02:38:32,766 --> 02:38:36,800
you'll find Indians achieving
extraordinary results everywhere.

2073
02:38:37,600 --> 02:38:39,733
Take our space sector, for example.

2074
02:38:42,200 --> 02:38:44,700
Previously, it was entirely
government-controlled.

2075
02:38:45,000 --> 02:38:49,500
But just a couple of years ago, I opened
it up to the private sector,

2076
02:38:49,700 --> 02:38:54,466
and now we already have 200 startups
working in space technology.

2077
02:38:55,800 --> 02:39:02,733
Moreover, our missions like Chandrayaan
are extremely cost-effective.

2078
02:39:03,633 --> 02:39:06,800
India's Chandrayaan mission cost
less than what

2079
02:39:06,800 --> 02:39:10,000
Hollywood spends making a single
blockbuster film!

2080
02:39:10,266 --> 02:39:14,000
So, when the world sees how cost-effective
our work is,

2081
02:39:14,000 --> 02:39:16,133
they naturally think, "Why not partner
with India?"

2082
02:39:16,400 --> 02:39:20,000
This automatically generates respect for
Indian talent globally.

2083
02:39:21,166 --> 02:39:27,933
I believe this is a hallmark of our
civilizational ethos.

2084
02:39:28,633 --> 02:39:31,033
- So you spoke about this human
intelligence.

2085
02:39:31,300 --> 02:39:36,700
Do you worry that AI, artificial
intelligence, will replace us humans?

2086
02:39:38,400 --> 02:39:40,500
- It's true that in every era,

2087
02:39:43,300 --> 02:39:46,666
a competitive atmosphere was created

2088
02:39:48,400 --> 02:39:50,900
between technology and humanity.

2089
02:39:52,133 --> 02:39:55,966
At times, it was even

2090
02:39:57,066 --> 02:39:59,300
portrayed as conflict.

2091
02:40:00,900 --> 02:40:05,433
It was often portrayed as if technology
would challenge human existence itself.

2092
02:40:06,200 --> 02:40:12,000
But every time, as technology advanced,
humans adapted and stayed a step ahead.

2093
02:40:12,333 --> 02:40:14,066
It has always been the case.

2094
02:40:14,466 --> 02:40:20,100
After all, it is humans who find the best
ways to use technology to their advantage.

2095
02:40:20,400 --> 02:40:25,200
And I believe that with AI, humans are now

2096
02:40:26,766 --> 02:40:31,233
being forced to reflect on
what it truly means to be human.

2097
02:40:31,433 --> 02:40:33,400
This is the real power of AI.

2098
02:40:34,500 --> 02:40:39,900
Because of the way AI functions, it has
challenged how we perceive work itself.

2099
02:40:41,100 --> 02:40:46,133
But human imagination is the fuel.

2100
02:40:48,166 --> 02:40:53,100
AI can create many things
based on that,

2101
02:40:53,200 --> 02:40:55,933
and in the future, it may
achieve even more.

2102
02:40:56,133 --> 02:40:59,733
Still, I firmly believe that no
technology can ever

2103
02:41:00,733 --> 02:41:04,933
replace the boundless creativity
and imagination of the human mind.

2104
02:41:05,300 --> 02:41:06,433
- I agree with you.

2105
02:41:07,200 --> 02:41:11,600
It does make me and a lot of people wonder
what makes human special

2106
02:41:11,600 --> 02:41:15,100
because it seems that there is a lot that
makes human special.

2107
02:41:15,833 --> 02:41:21,900
The imagination, the creativity, the
consciousness, the ability to be afraid,

2108
02:41:21,933 --> 02:41:25,200
to love, to dream,

2109
02:41:25,433 --> 02:41:29,500
to think outside of the box, outside of
the box, of the box, of the box,

2110
02:41:30,200 --> 02:41:32,200
take risks, all of those things.

2111
02:41:32,700 --> 02:41:36,333
- Now, look, humans have an innate ability
to care for each other,

2112
02:41:38,133 --> 02:41:41,100
the natural tendency to be concerned about
one another.

2113
02:41:42,100 --> 02:41:45,900
Now, can someone tell me, is AI capable of
this?

2114
02:41:46,400 --> 02:41:49,533
- This is one of the big open questions of
the 21st century.

2115
02:41:51,300 --> 02:41:56,200
Every year you host the "Pariksha Pe
Charcha"

2116
02:41:56,200 --> 02:41:58,366
where you interact directly with young
students

2117
02:41:58,400 --> 02:42:01,100
and give them advice on how to prepare for
exams.

2118
02:42:01,300 --> 02:42:04,900
I watched a bunch of them so you you give
advice on

2119
02:42:05,300 --> 02:42:08,700
how to succeed in exams, how to manage
stress, all those kind of things.

2120
02:42:09,300 --> 02:42:11,900
Can you explain on a high level

2121
02:42:12,400 --> 02:42:16,600
the different exams that students in India
need to take in their education journey,

2122
02:42:16,900 --> 02:42:18,500
and why it's so stressful?

2123
02:42:18,900 --> 02:42:23,300
- By and large, a strange mindset has
developed in society today.

2124
02:42:24,933 --> 02:42:29,900
Even schools measure their success by
students' rankings.

2125
02:42:31,200 --> 02:42:35,400
Families, too, feel pride when their child
achieves a high rank,

2126
02:42:35,433 --> 02:42:39,933
because they believe it improves their
educational and social status.

2127
02:42:40,600 --> 02:42:44,800
This mentality has resulted in increased
pressure on children.

2128
02:42:46,600 --> 02:42:52,300
Kids also began feeling that their entire
lives depend on 10th and 12th grade exams.

2129
02:42:53,200 --> 02:42:55,966
We've introduced significant changes in
our

2130
02:42:56,000 --> 02:42:58,333
new education policy to address this
issue.

2131
02:42:58,866 --> 02:43:03,600
But until those changes take effect on the
ground, I feel another responsibility:

2132
02:43:07,900 --> 02:43:11,000
If our children face challenges, it's my
duty to listen to them,

2133
02:43:11,433 --> 02:43:13,566
understand them and ease their burden.

2134
02:43:14,200 --> 02:43:17,333
In a way, when I conduct
"Pariksha Pe Charcha,"

2135
02:43:18,200 --> 02:43:21,100
I get insights directly
from the students,

2136
02:43:21,500 --> 02:43:24,800
understand their parents' mindset,

2137
02:43:25,333 --> 02:43:29,233
as well as the perspectives of people in
the educational field.

2138
02:43:30,000 --> 02:43:36,133
So, these discussions don't just benefit
the students; they benefit me too.

2139
02:43:37,600 --> 02:43:43,466
Exams are valuable for assessing knowledge
in a specific domain,

2140
02:43:44,333 --> 02:43:48,533
but they can't become the sole measure of
someone's overall potential.

2141
02:43:49,400 --> 02:43:54,100
Many people may not score high
academically,

2142
02:43:54,300 --> 02:43:56,866
yet can hit a century in
cricket because

2143
02:43:57,400 --> 02:43:59,733
that's where their true strength
lies.

2144
02:44:00,100 --> 02:44:06,600
When the focus shifts to actual learning,
scores tend to naturally improve.

2145
02:44:08,200 --> 02:44:12,833
I remember when I was a student, I had a
teacher

2146
02:44:14,200 --> 02:44:17,500
whose learning techniques still greatly
appeal to me today.

2147
02:44:18,200 --> 02:44:20,633
He would give us children specific
instructions.

2148
02:44:21,200 --> 02:44:27,133
To one child, he would say, "Tomorrow,
bring exactly 10 chickpeas from home."

2149
02:44:28,333 --> 02:44:34,133
To another, he might request, "Bring 15
grains of rice, no more, no less."

2150
02:44:34,733 --> 02:44:40,133
A third child could be told, "Bring 21
moong beans, precisely that number."

2151
02:44:40,300 --> 02:44:43,600
Different students got different
quantities and varieties.

2152
02:44:44,100 --> 02:44:47,400
So, each child would think,
"I need to get exactly ten,"

2153
02:44:47,533 --> 02:44:51,833
and counting them at home helped them
memorize numbers naturally.

2154
02:44:52,400 --> 02:44:54,600
Then, they'd learn what chickpeas were,

2155
02:44:55,133 --> 02:44:58,100
and after returning to school,
they'd pool it all.

2156
02:44:58,233 --> 02:45:01,733
The teacher would then ask,
"Take out ten chickpeas,

2157
02:45:01,800 --> 02:45:04,333
three chickpeas, two moong beans..."

2158
02:45:04,600 --> 02:45:06,100
This way, children learned math

2159
02:45:06,133 --> 02:45:09,500
and could identify chickpeas
and moong beans effortlessly.

2160
02:45:09,633 --> 02:45:12,700
I'm talking about early childhood
education here.

2161
02:45:13,433 --> 02:45:17,900
Such learning techniques educate children
without burdening them,

2162
02:45:17,900 --> 02:45:21,700
and we've incorporated similar methods
into our new education policy.

2163
02:45:22,100 --> 02:45:26,400
When I was in school,
I observed one of my teachers

2164
02:45:27,166 --> 02:45:29,333
using an innovative idea.

2165
02:45:29,800 --> 02:45:33,900
On his very first day, he placed a diary
on the table and said,

2166
02:45:34,933 --> 02:45:37,500
Whoever arrives earliest each morning

2167
02:45:38,000 --> 02:45:42,833
will write one sentence in this diary,
along with their name.

2168
02:45:44,900 --> 02:45:50,600
The next student would then need to write
a related sentence.

2169
02:45:52,300 --> 02:45:58,000
At first, I'd rush to school very early
every day. Why?

2170
02:45:58,533 --> 02:46:01,100
So that I could write the first sentence.

2171
02:46:01,833 --> 02:46:04,733
I once wrote something like,

2172
02:46:05,233 --> 02:46:09,133
"Today's sunrise was magnificent;

2173
02:46:09,800 --> 02:46:11,800
it filled me with energy."

2174
02:46:12,133 --> 02:46:16,433
I'd write my name, and whoever arrived
after me had to

2175
02:46:16,466 --> 02:46:19,533
write something connected to the sunrise
as well.

2176
02:46:20,533 --> 02:46:24,233
After a few days, I realized

2177
02:46:24,966 --> 02:46:27,700
my creativity
wasn't improving much from this.

2178
02:46:28,500 --> 02:46:32,833
Why? Because I'd arrive with a fixed
thought already in mind

2179
02:46:33,033 --> 02:46:34,600
and simply write
it down.

2180
02:46:34,966 --> 02:46:37,866
So, I decided I'd start
going last instead.

2181
02:46:38,900 --> 02:46:43,133
What happened then was that I'd read what
others had written first,

2182
02:46:44,633 --> 02:46:47,433
and then try to give my very best.

2183
02:46:48,033 --> 02:46:51,300
As a result, my creativity began to
improve even more.

2184
02:46:52,533 --> 02:46:55,800
Sometimes, teachers do these small,

2185
02:46:56,233 --> 02:46:59,633
simple activities that
greatly impact your life.

2186
02:47:00,700 --> 02:47:05,733
These experiences, combined with
my own background

2187
02:47:06,733 --> 02:47:08,800
in organizational work,

2188
02:47:09,400 --> 02:47:14,133
made human resource development a key area
of focus for me.

2189
02:47:14,300 --> 02:47:18,466
That's why I engage with children through
events once or twice each year.

2190
02:47:18,600 --> 02:47:21,533
And over time, these efforts have resulted
in a book

2191
02:47:21,933 --> 02:47:27,100
that's benefiting thousands of children,
serving as a valuable reference for them.

2192
02:47:27,433 --> 02:47:34,200
- Can you speak a little bit more by way
of advice to students

2193
02:47:34,233 --> 02:47:40,100
of how to be successful on their path in
their career, how to find the career

2194
02:47:40,733 --> 02:47:46,000
and how to find success, in India, and
just to all the people across the world

2195
02:47:46,033 --> 02:47:48,600
who find inspiration in your words?

2196
02:47:50,000 --> 02:47:54,733
- I believe that whatever task you get,

2197
02:47:57,566 --> 02:48:04,133
if you perform that task with complete
dedication and sincerity,

2198
02:48:05,900 --> 02:48:12,433
they inevitably become an expert sooner or
later,

2199
02:48:14,600 --> 02:48:18,133
and their enhanced capabilities

2200
02:48:19,366 --> 02:48:21,700
open doors to success.

2201
02:48:23,333 --> 02:48:24,900
While working,

2202
02:48:26,800 --> 02:48:30,533
one must continually strive
to improve their skills

2203
02:48:31,733 --> 02:48:38,200
and should never underestimate their
ability to learn.

2204
02:48:39,133 --> 02:48:44,400
When someone constantly neglects their
learning ability, they limit their growth.

2205
02:48:44,700 --> 02:48:50,200
But those who look beyond their tasks, and
observe what others around them are doing,

2206
02:48:50,800 --> 02:48:53,733
their capacity can double or even triple.

2207
02:48:54,233 --> 02:48:56,633
To young people, I'd say this clearly:

2208
02:48:57,633 --> 02:49:02,500
There’s no need to feel discouraged,
there’s certainly

2209
02:49:04,033 --> 02:49:07,600
some task out there destined just for you.
Don't worry.

2210
02:49:09,200 --> 02:49:13,400
Focus on enhancing your skills, and
opportunities will come.

2211
02:49:14,900 --> 02:49:19,666
You may think: "I wanted to be a doctor
but became a teacher. My life is wasted."

2212
02:49:19,700 --> 02:49:23,433
Thinking like that won't help you at all.
Alright, you didn't become a doctor,

2213
02:49:23,633 --> 02:49:26,333
but as a teacher, you can shape a hundred
doctors.

2214
02:49:28,700 --> 02:49:34,033
If you had become a doctor, you'd serve
only your patients, but now, as a teacher,

2215
02:49:34,100 --> 02:49:37,500
you can inspire students to fulfill their
dreams of becoming doctors,

2216
02:49:37,633 --> 02:49:42,000
so that both you and your students can
together serve millions of patients.

2217
02:49:42,600 --> 02:49:45,300
Then, he gains a new perspective on life:

2218
02:49:45,400 --> 02:49:48,400
“I couldn't become a doctor, so I was
miserable,

2219
02:49:48,533 --> 02:49:50,700
and I was unhappy being a teacher.

2220
02:49:51,000 --> 02:49:53,766
But now I realize, as a teacher, I can
create doctors.”

2221
02:49:54,200 --> 02:50:00,033
Connecting your life to a greater purpose
brings a sense of inspiration and meaning

2222
02:50:00,300 --> 02:50:06,500
I have always believed that God has given
everyone unique capabilities

2223
02:50:08,700 --> 02:50:11,833
Never lose faith in your own abilities;

2224
02:50:12,733 --> 02:50:16,100
You should always maintain trust in your
own abilities.

2225
02:50:16,200 --> 02:50:20,233
Keep believing in yourself, and trust that
when the opportunity comes,

2226
02:50:20,266 --> 02:50:22,533
you'll perform,
and you'll succeed.

2227
02:50:22,566 --> 02:50:25,533
That confidence makes a
person deliver results.

2228
02:50:26,066 --> 02:50:29,500
- How did those students deal with stress,

2229
02:50:29,733 --> 02:50:32,533
with struggle, with difficulties along
that path?

2230
02:50:33,566 --> 02:50:37,733
- Parents must first understand that life
is not just about taking exams.

2231
02:50:39,600 --> 02:50:42,700
Families should understand, that their
children aren’t

2232
02:50:42,733 --> 02:50:44,433
trophies meant to be
displayed

2233
02:50:46,033 --> 02:50:48,233
or models to show off in society.

2234
02:50:48,266 --> 02:50:51,333
It’s not about saying,
"Look, my kid scores so high!"

2235
02:50:51,666 --> 02:50:55,233
Parents really need to stop using their
kids just as status symbols.

2236
02:50:55,833 --> 02:51:01,566
Secondly, students should always keep
themselves well-prepared beforehand.

2237
02:51:01,866 --> 02:51:07,633
Only then can they appear for exams
feeling stress-free and confident.

2238
02:51:07,733 --> 02:51:11,566
They should have complete trust in
themselves and their abilities.

2239
02:51:11,933 --> 02:51:16,033
Sometimes I see students panic over the
smallest issues during exams,

2240
02:51:17,033 --> 02:51:19,166
they take papers or other things

2241
02:51:19,233 --> 02:51:23,033
and when their pen suddenly stops working,
causing anxiety.

2242
02:51:23,300 --> 02:51:25,366
Sometimes they feel uneasy, thinking,

2243
02:51:25,366 --> 02:51:27,633
"Oh no, I don’t like sitting next to this
person."

2244
02:51:27,966 --> 02:51:32,933
If the bench wobbles, their whole
attention goes there, indicating self-doubt.

2245
02:51:33,433 --> 02:51:36,933
Those lacking confidence constantly keep
looking for distractions.

2246
02:51:37,533 --> 02:51:42,966
But if you're confident and have genuinely
worked hard, just take a minute.

2247
02:51:43,033 --> 02:51:47,733
Take some deep breaths, relax your mind,
and refocus your attention calmly.

2248
02:51:48,133 --> 02:51:52,633
Slowly read through the questions and
allocate your time systematically,

2249
02:51:53,033 --> 02:51:56,633
I have this amount of time, I'll dedicate
these minutes per question.

2250
02:51:57,233 --> 02:52:01,133
In my experience, students who regularly
practice writing test papers

2251
02:52:01,833 --> 02:52:06,233
can easily overcome such situations
without any trouble at all.

2252
02:52:06,666 --> 02:52:09,233
- And you said, always focus on learning.

2253
02:52:09,666 --> 02:52:11,933
What's your approach to learning?

2254
02:52:14,133 --> 02:52:16,166
What advice can you give on how to learn
best,

2255
02:52:16,366 --> 02:52:18,533
not just when you are young, but
throughout your life?

2256
02:52:19,633 --> 02:52:22,733
- Let me share a personal example with
you.

2257
02:52:24,533 --> 02:52:29,100
I used to learn a lot from reading, but
these days,

2258
02:52:30,400 --> 02:52:35,833
more and more,
I learn by being fully present.

2259
02:52:36,133 --> 02:52:40,300
Whenever I meet someone, I am fully
present in the moment.

2260
02:52:40,633 --> 02:52:42,933
I give them my full attention.

2261
02:52:43,500 --> 02:52:47,433
This complete focus allows me to grasp new
concepts quickly.

2262
02:52:48,266 --> 02:52:52,366
When I'm with you, I'm fully present,
grounded in the moment.

2263
02:52:53,066 --> 02:52:56,566
No calls or messages can pull me away from
this moment with you.

2264
02:52:57,333 --> 02:53:00,066
I am fully present, focused on the here
and now.

2265
02:53:01,100 --> 02:53:05,466
That’s why I always believe this is a
habit everyone should embrace.

2266
02:53:05,966 --> 02:53:09,400
It will sharpen your mind and improve your
learning ability.

2267
02:53:09,800 --> 02:53:13,766
Besides, knowledge alone cannot light the
way.

2268
02:53:14,366 --> 02:53:16,966
You must immerse yourself in the flow of
practice.

2269
02:53:17,600 --> 02:53:22,000
You cannot master driving merely by
reading the life stories of great drivers.

2270
02:53:22,466 --> 02:53:26,133
You must get behind the wheel and take the
road yourself.

2271
02:53:26,466 --> 02:53:28,766
You must dare to take
risks.

2272
02:53:29,166 --> 02:53:34,166
You can never master the road if fear of
accident or death holds you back.

2273
02:53:35,900 --> 02:53:40,000
I truly believe that those who live in the
present,

2274
02:53:40,200 --> 02:53:43,366
are the ones who live life to the
fullest.

2275
02:53:44,266 --> 02:53:50,000
That’s because they know that every moment
lived has already slipped into the past.

2276
02:53:53,366 --> 02:53:57,000
So you must embrace the moment before it
fades into the past.

2277
02:53:57,866 --> 02:54:01,566
Otherwise, chasing the future only turns
the present into the past.

2278
02:54:02,066 --> 02:54:03,800
It's not a trade worth making.

2279
02:54:04,666 --> 02:54:08,866
Most people stress so much about the
future

2280
02:54:08,866 --> 02:54:11,566
that their present quietly slips
away.

2281
02:54:11,966 --> 02:54:17,666
Before they know it, the moment has
already faded into the past.

2282
02:54:18,900 --> 02:54:24,466
- Yeah, I've heard a lot of stories of you
having meetings with people, and it's—

2283
02:54:25,066 --> 02:54:27,700
usually all the distractions are—

2284
02:54:27,866 --> 02:54:31,166
There are no distractions. There are just
two human beings, just like this.

2285
02:54:31,366 --> 02:54:35,433
And just focused on the moment
and the interaction,

2286
02:54:35,466 --> 02:54:36,600
and that's a really beautiful thing.

2287
02:54:36,666 --> 02:54:40,800
And today really is a gift that you would
give that focus to me, so thank you.

2288
02:54:42,600 --> 02:54:45,766
Let me ask, maybe, a difficult, maybe, a
human question.

2289
02:54:46,866 --> 02:54:50,200
Do you contemplate your mortality? Are you
afraid of death?

2290
02:54:54,066 --> 02:54:56,000
- Can I ask you a question instead?

2291
02:54:56,833 --> 02:54:57,733
- Sure.

2292
02:54:57,933 --> 02:55:01,033
- I have a very interesting question.

2293
02:55:02,000 --> 02:55:08,233
Life and death are two sides of a coin,
but which of the two is more certain?

2294
02:55:09,000 --> 02:55:10,166
- Death.

2295
02:55:10,300 --> 02:55:12,133
- Exactly.

2296
02:55:12,133 --> 02:55:14,833
Now, with that out of the way,

2297
02:55:16,133 --> 02:55:21,166
we know for a fact that life itself is a
whispered promise of death.

2298
02:55:21,766 --> 02:55:25,000
and yet, life is also destined to
flourish.

2299
02:55:26,233 --> 02:55:31,633
So, again, in the dance of life and death,
only death is certain.

2300
02:55:33,000 --> 02:55:35,600
So, why fear what is certain?

2301
02:55:36,933 --> 02:55:41,900
That’s why you must embrace life, instead
of fretting over death.

2302
02:55:43,000 --> 02:55:47,533
That's how life will evolve and flourish,
for it is uncertain.

2303
02:55:48,100 --> 02:55:51,933
That’s why you must commit to enriching,

2304
02:55:52,100 --> 02:55:56,333
refining, and elevating your life

2305
02:55:56,666 --> 02:56:03,400
so you can live fully and with a purpose
before death comes knocking.

2306
02:56:04,033 --> 02:56:06,933
That's why you must let go of the fear of
death.

2307
02:56:07,300 --> 02:56:09,966
After all, death is inevitable,

2308
02:56:10,133 --> 02:56:13,000
and there's no use worrying
about when it will arrive.

2309
02:56:13,600 --> 02:56:16,000
It will arrive when it's meant to.

2310
02:56:17,433 --> 02:56:21,833
- What gives you hope about the future,
not just of India,

2311
02:56:22,100 --> 02:56:26,000
but all of human civilization—all of us
humans here on Earth?

2312
02:56:27,700 --> 02:56:31,000
- Well, I am an optimist at heart.

2313
02:56:32,033 --> 02:56:37,666
Pessimism and negativity are simply not
ingrained in my mindset;

2314
02:56:38,400 --> 02:56:41,000
they don't align
with the way I think.

2315
02:56:41,700 --> 02:56:45,433
That’s why I always gravitate toward the
bright side instead.

2316
02:56:47,900 --> 02:56:53,233
If we take a moment to reflect on the
history of mankind,

2317
02:56:54,800 --> 02:56:59,400
we see the incredible crises humans have
overcome with resilience and strength.

2318
02:57:00,933 --> 02:57:05,900
We also see the major changes humanity has
embraced to evolve with the times.

2319
02:57:07,000 --> 02:57:10,300
And this continuous transformation has
carried on for millennia.

2320
02:57:10,900 --> 02:57:13,766
In every era, it is in human nature to
adapt

2321
02:57:13,800 --> 02:57:15,600
to the ever-flowing current of
change.

2322
02:57:16,100 --> 02:57:21,333
And while our progress has gone through
cycles of ups and downs,

2323
02:57:22,233 --> 02:57:26,200
it is those people who can break free from
the constraints

2324
02:57:28,433 --> 02:57:33,100
of these historical cycles and outdated
thinking patterns.

2325
02:57:35,200 --> 02:57:41,200
It is they who can help humanity achieve
extraordinary positive breakthroughs,

2326
02:57:41,666 --> 02:57:45,400
with an unshackled speed and grace,

2327
02:57:47,133 --> 02:57:51,133
Transcending the limitations of the old
way of doing things,

2328
02:57:51,466 --> 02:57:54,733
by embracing change.

2329
02:57:56,600 --> 02:57:59,833
- In this moment, I was wondering if you
could guide me,

2330
02:58:01,000 --> 02:58:05,433
perhaps, through a Hindu prayer
or meditation for a few moments.

2331
02:58:06,000 --> 02:58:09,700
I learned—

2332
02:58:10,500 --> 02:58:14,200
I'm trying to learn the Gayatri Mantra.

2333
02:58:16,733 --> 02:58:19,266
And in my fast, I was trying to do the
chants.

2334
02:58:19,300 --> 02:58:21,633
Perhaps I could try chanting, and
you could—

2335
02:58:22,100 --> 02:58:25,100
tell me about the importance of this
mantra and maybe

2336
02:58:25,133 --> 02:58:29,100
others in your life, in
your spirituality.

2337
02:58:29,700 --> 02:58:30,800
Should I try?

2338
02:58:31,266 --> 02:58:33,100
- Yes, please.

2339
02:58:33,433 --> 02:58:37,166
- <i>Om Bhur Bhuvah Swah</i>

2340
02:58:37,366 --> 02:58:40,700
<i>Tat Savitur Varenyam</i>

2341
02:58:41,000 --> 02:58:44,466
<i>Bhargo Devasya Dheemahi</i>

2342
02:58:44,666 --> 02:58:48,233
<i>Dhiyo Yo Nah Prachodayaat</i>

2343
02:58:48,900 --> 02:58:51,100
How did I do? It's ok?

2344
02:58:51,366 --> 02:58:53,233
- You did great!

2345
02:58:53,700 --> 02:58:56,100
<i>Om Bhur Bhuvah Swah</i>

2346
02:58:56,333 --> 02:58:57,966
<i>Tat Savitur Varenyam</i>

2347
02:58:58,000 --> 02:59:01,000
<i>Bhargo Devasya Dheemahi</i>
<i>Dhiyo Yo Nah Prachodayaat</i>

2348
02:59:01,933 --> 02:59:07,366
This mantra is dedicated to the radient
power of the Sun

2349
02:59:08,866 --> 02:59:12,800
and is considered a powerful tool for
spiritual enlightenment.

2350
02:59:13,400 --> 02:59:18,600
Many mantras in Hindu philosophy are
deeply intertwined,

2351
02:59:21,133 --> 02:59:27,433
In some intricate and interesting ways,
with science and nature.

2352
02:59:29,000 --> 02:59:32,200
Each woven into different facets of life.

2353
02:59:32,900 --> 02:59:35,966
Chanting mantras on a daily basis

2354
02:59:37,133 --> 02:59:40,800
brings profound and
lasting benefits.

2355
02:59:41,433 --> 02:59:46,300
- In your own spirituality, in your quiet
moments, when you are with God,

2356
02:59:47,500 --> 02:59:50,633
where does your mind go, what role do
mantras play

2357
02:59:52,400 --> 02:59:55,700
when you're fasting, when you're just
alone with yourself?

2358
02:59:56,933 --> 03:00:03,800
- The word meditation has been overused to
the point that it feels like a cliché.

2359
03:00:05,000 --> 03:00:10,300
In Indian languages, we usually refer to
it as "Dhyaan".

2360
03:00:12,033 --> 03:00:18,300
If I associate Dhyaan to meditation, it
might seem burdensome to some.

2361
03:00:18,733 --> 03:00:23,933
One might think: "This is too difficult.
I'm not an enlightened being."

2362
03:00:24,633 --> 03:00:31,400
But it's not rocket science. It just means
freeing yourself from distraction.

2363
03:00:32,000 --> 03:00:36,000
For example, even when you're in class,

2364
03:00:36,633 --> 03:00:40,300
your mind wanders to recess.

2365
03:00:41,333 --> 03:00:44,000
All you think about is lunch, not the
lesson.

2366
03:00:45,333 --> 03:00:48,800
Meditation is simply being present in the
moment.

2367
03:00:49,200 --> 03:00:53,533
I recall an incident from my time living
in the Himalayas.

2368
03:00:54,800 --> 03:00:57,133
There, I encountered this wise sage.

2369
03:00:58,200 --> 03:01:04,500
He taught me a simple, practical
technique. It was nothing spiritual.

2370
03:01:05,700 --> 03:01:08,100
There are several little streams in the
Himalayas.

2371
03:01:09,700 --> 03:01:15,900
He positioned a large leaf

2372
03:01:17,400 --> 03:01:22,200
to catch water
from one of those streams.

2373
03:01:23,533 --> 03:01:27,800
And placed an up-side-down bowl below.

2374
03:01:28,600 --> 03:01:32,066
So water would drip rhythmically from the
leaf onto the bowl.

2375
03:01:33,033 --> 03:01:37,833
He asked me to focus only
on the dripping water,

2376
03:01:38,000 --> 03:01:40,133
ignoring all other sounds.

2377
03:01:41,733 --> 03:01:45,900
Ignore the chirping birds and the soft
rustle of the breeze.

2378
03:01:47,066 --> 03:01:52,900
He would place the leaf, and I would
meditate there for hours.

2379
03:01:53,700 --> 03:01:58,300
I felt my mind slowly tuning in to

2380
03:01:58,500 --> 03:02:04,133
the rhythmic sounds of the water droplets
falling onto the bowl,

2381
03:02:04,900 --> 03:02:08,100
like a melody guiding me into deep focus.

2382
03:02:08,800 --> 03:02:13,733
And it's not like I was chanting mantras
or reciting God’s name.

2383
03:02:16,600 --> 03:02:18,633
I like to call it the divine resonance.

2384
03:02:19,333 --> 03:02:22,500
It was by tuning into that divine
resonance

2385
03:02:22,700 --> 03:02:25,433
that I learned the art of
concentration.

2386
03:02:26,200 --> 03:02:28,400
This practice slowly evolved into
meditation.

2387
03:02:29,900 --> 03:02:33,700
Sometimes, you happen to stay at a fancy
hotel.

2388
03:02:35,400 --> 03:02:37,433
You get a lavish, luxurious room.

2389
03:02:38,033 --> 03:02:43,400
The decor is impeccable, and you have been
wholeheartedly fasting.

2390
03:02:44,033 --> 03:02:47,800
But there's a dripping faucet in the
bathroom.

2391
03:02:48,833 --> 03:02:55,833
That faint sound is enough to make a
luxurious room feel worthless.

2392
03:02:57,433 --> 03:03:03,433
At times, we realize the value of
concentration

2393
03:03:04,100 --> 03:03:06,100
in life’s inner journey.

2394
03:03:06,933 --> 03:03:11,033
We come to appreciate the difference a lit
bit of concentration can make.

2395
03:03:11,400 --> 03:03:17,000
One very interesting concept comes to mind
from our scriptures.

2396
03:03:21,500 --> 03:03:26,933
Since we spoke about life and death, I
would like to quote a mantra.

2397
03:03:27,500 --> 03:03:34,100
<i>Om purnamadah purnamidam</i>
<i>purnatmapurnamudacyate</i>

2398
03:03:35,100 --> 03:03:39,500
in other words, all life is part of a
complete circle.

2399
03:03:40,333 --> 03:03:44,500
And this mantra emphasizes the path to
achieve that completeness.

2400
03:03:44,633 --> 03:03:50,700
Similarly, Hindus never focus solely on
individual well-being.

2401
03:03:50,833 --> 03:03:54,100
<i>Sarve bhavantu sukhinah </i>
<i>sarve santu niraamayaah.</i>

2402
03:03:54,500 --> 03:03:58,633
In other words, we wish for the well-being
and prosperity of all.

2403
03:03:59,000 --> 03:04:03,400
<i>Sarve bhadraanni pashyantu</i>
<i>Maa kashcid duhkha bhaag bhavet</i>

2404
03:04:04,033 --> 03:04:10,733
this mantra encompasses the idea of
universal well-being and prosperity.

2405
03:04:11,100 --> 03:04:15,500
And you know how this mantra ends?
<i>Om shaantih, shaantih, shaantih</i>

2406
03:04:16,000 --> 03:04:20,333
every Hindu mantra ends on the same note.
"Peace, peace, peace."

2407
03:04:22,266 --> 03:04:25,333
These ancient and powerful rituals, born
in India,

2408
03:04:28,300 --> 03:04:34,200
have emerged from thousands of years of
the spiritual practice of sages.

2409
03:04:34,533 --> 03:04:37,100
They connect us to the essence of life.

2410
03:04:37,500 --> 03:04:39,566
- <i>Shaantih, shaantih, shaantih.</i>

2411
03:04:39,600 --> 03:04:40,600
- Uh-huh.

2412
03:04:40,600 --> 03:04:44,233
- Thank you for this honor, thank you for
this incredible conversation.

2413
03:04:44,333 --> 03:04:46,833
Thank you for welcoming me to India,

2414
03:04:47,033 --> 03:04:51,566
and I can't wait to break the fast with
some Indian food tomorrow.

2415
03:04:52,800 --> 03:04:55,000
Thank you so much, Prime Minister. This
was an honor.

2416
03:04:55,900 --> 03:05:00,200
- I am thankful for the opportunity to
have this conversation with you.

2417
03:05:01,000 --> 03:05:05,100
After fasting for two days, I recommend
you ease into eating slowly.

2418
03:05:05,933 --> 03:05:10,233
And I hope you reap great benefits from
this fasting experience.

2419
03:05:11,700 --> 03:05:13,866
I’ve explored several new realms of
thought

2420
03:05:13,900 --> 03:05:16,466
for the first time ever with you
today.

2421
03:05:16,700 --> 03:05:22,966
I had long kept those thoughts tucked away
within myself.

2422
03:05:23,566 --> 03:05:26,166
But today, you've brought those thoughts
to light.

2423
03:05:26,766 --> 03:05:30,266
I hope—
- Thank you.

2424
03:05:30,266 --> 03:05:34,766
- I hope your viewers may enjoy this. It
was a great pleasure speaking with you.

2425
03:05:36,100 --> 03:05:37,000
- Thank you.

2426
03:05:37,033 --> 03:05:37,700
- Thank you.

2427
03:05:38,800 --> 03:05:41,100
Thank you for listening
to this conversation

2428
03:05:41,100 --> 03:05:44,166
with Prime Minister Narendra Modi.

2429
03:05:44,166 --> 03:05:47,666
And now let me answer some
questions and try to reflect on

2430
03:05:47,866 --> 03:05:50,500
and articulate some things
I've been thinking about.

2431
03:05:50,500 --> 03:05:51,933
If you would like to submit questions

2432
03:05:51,933 --> 03:05:55,200
or get in touch with
me for whatever reason,

2433
03:05:55,200 --> 03:05:57,366
go to lexfridman.com/contact.

2434
03:05:58,300 --> 03:06:01,133
First, let me give a shout out

2435
03:06:01,133 --> 03:06:04,166
to the amazing team
around the Prime Minister.

2436
03:06:04,166 --> 03:06:07,966
Everyone was super kind,
excellent at what they do,

2437
03:06:07,966 --> 03:06:10,066
efficient, great communication,

2438
03:06:10,066 --> 03:06:13,033
and just great people all around.

2439
03:06:13,033 --> 03:06:15,800
And since I spoke English

2440
03:06:15,800 --> 03:06:18,466
and Prime Minister Modi spoke Hindi,

2441
03:06:18,466 --> 03:06:21,633
I have to comment on the interpreter

2442
03:06:21,633 --> 03:06:25,233
who was doing simultaneous
interpreting for both of us.

2443
03:06:25,233 --> 03:06:27,966
She was absolutely amazing.

2444
03:06:27,966 --> 03:06:29,700
I can't sing her enough praises.

2445
03:06:29,700 --> 03:06:33,600
From the equipment used, to
the quality of the translation,

2446
03:06:33,600 --> 03:06:36,666
to just the human touch of it all.

2447
03:06:36,666 --> 03:06:40,900
And in general, my travels
around Delhi and India

2448
03:06:40,900 --> 03:06:43,733
revealed to me some early glimpses

2449
03:06:43,733 --> 03:06:48,033
of what felt like another world,
almost like another planet,

2450
03:06:48,033 --> 03:06:51,533
different culturally from
anything I've experienced before.

2451
03:06:51,533 --> 03:06:53,933
A chaos of human interactions,

2452
03:06:53,933 --> 03:06:57,400
out there, big dynamic
personalities and characters.

2453
03:06:58,466 --> 03:07:02,033
Obviously, India's composed
of many distinct subcultures,

2454
03:07:02,033 --> 03:07:04,700
and Delhi represents just one slice.

2455
03:07:04,700 --> 03:07:07,300
Much like neither New York

2456
03:07:07,300 --> 03:07:10,866
or Texas or Iowa alone represent America.

2457
03:07:10,866 --> 03:07:13,800
They're all different flavors of America.

2458
03:07:13,800 --> 03:07:17,400
On my visit, I walked around
and rode rickshaws everywhere,

2459
03:07:17,400 --> 03:07:19,833
just aimlessly wandering the streets,

2460
03:07:19,833 --> 03:07:22,866
looking to talk to people about life.

2461
03:07:23,700 --> 03:07:26,200
Of course, like many places on Earth,

2462
03:07:26,200 --> 03:07:28,300
there are always some people,

2463
03:07:28,300 --> 03:07:30,966
especially those that
have something to sell,

2464
03:07:30,966 --> 03:07:33,066
who will at first see me as a tourist,

2465
03:07:33,066 --> 03:07:36,700
a foreign traveler, one
with some money to spend.

2466
03:07:36,700 --> 03:07:40,633
Like always, I avoided
such shallow interactions

2467
03:07:40,633 --> 03:07:42,433
and went straight past the small talk

2468
03:07:42,433 --> 03:07:45,266
to the meaningful conversations,

2469
03:07:45,266 --> 03:07:47,433
shooting the shit about what they love,

2470
03:07:47,433 --> 03:07:49,933
what they fear, what kind of hardship

2471
03:07:49,933 --> 03:07:52,600
and triumph they've
experienced in their lives.

2472
03:07:52,600 --> 03:07:56,966
I think the cool thing about
people, anywhere on Earth,

2473
03:07:56,966 --> 03:08:00,700
is they quickly do see the real you,

2474
03:08:00,700 --> 03:08:04,066
past the facades that strangers
put up for each other,

2475
03:08:04,066 --> 03:08:08,466
if you're vulnerable and
honest enough to let them,

2476
03:08:08,466 --> 03:08:10,900
and I try to do just that.

2477
03:08:10,900 --> 03:08:13,566
And I should say that for the most part,

2478
03:08:13,566 --> 03:08:16,966
everyone was super kind
in the genuine human way,

2479
03:08:16,966 --> 03:08:18,933
even when they didn't speak English,

2480
03:08:18,933 --> 03:08:21,166
it was always easy to understand.

2481
03:08:21,166 --> 03:08:24,233
Probably more than any other
people's I've interacted with,

2482
03:08:24,233 --> 03:08:27,833
in India, people's eyes,
faces, body language,

2483
03:08:27,833 --> 03:08:30,033
all communicated a lot of information,

2484
03:08:30,033 --> 03:08:33,666
a lot of emotion, not reserved at all.

2485
03:08:33,666 --> 03:08:36,500
When I travel through
Eastern Europe, for example,

2486
03:08:36,500 --> 03:08:39,833
in contrast, reading a
person is much tougher.

2487
03:08:39,833 --> 03:08:42,500
The meme does have some truth to it.

2488
03:08:42,500 --> 03:08:43,833
There's often a protective layer

2489
03:08:43,833 --> 03:08:47,666
between the heart of the
person and the outside world.

2490
03:08:47,666 --> 03:08:50,766
In India, it's all there on full display.

2491
03:08:51,600 --> 03:08:54,033
So I had a lot of epic conversations

2492
03:08:54,033 --> 03:08:56,900
and interactions as I walked around Deli

2493
03:08:56,900 --> 03:08:58,700
for a couple of weeks.

2494
03:08:58,700 --> 03:09:02,166
In general, on the
topic of reading people,

2495
03:09:02,166 --> 03:09:06,133
I do believe the eyes can
often say more than words can.

2496
03:09:06,133 --> 03:09:09,366
We humans are a fascinating bunch.

2497
03:09:09,366 --> 03:09:11,700
There really is a deep, turbulent ocean

2498
03:09:11,700 --> 03:09:14,533
behind the surface
waves we show the world.

2499
03:09:14,533 --> 03:09:17,466
In some sense, what I try
to do in conversations,

2500
03:09:17,466 --> 03:09:20,666
on and off the mic, is
to get to that depth.

2501
03:09:20,666 --> 03:09:23,533
Anyway, the few weeks I spent in India

2502
03:09:23,533 --> 03:09:25,366
were a magical experience.

2503
03:09:25,366 --> 03:09:27,966
Traffic alone was a wild time,

2504
03:09:27,966 --> 03:09:31,866
like the world's most difficult
test for self-driving cars.

2505
03:09:32,766 --> 03:09:37,100
It reminded me of watching
nature documentary videos

2506
03:09:37,100 --> 03:09:41,033
of swarms of fish, when
it's thousands of them

2507
03:09:41,033 --> 03:09:43,766
swimming around at insane speeds,

2508
03:09:43,766 --> 03:09:46,866
seemingly in complete chaos.

2509
03:09:46,866 --> 03:09:49,033
And yet, when looking at
the big picture of it,

2510
03:09:49,033 --> 03:09:51,766
it all works like a
perfectly tuned orchestra.

2511
03:09:52,733 --> 03:09:55,866
I will most certainly travel around India

2512
03:09:55,866 --> 03:09:58,266
with my friend Paul
Rosolie in the near future,

2513
03:09:58,266 --> 03:09:59,733
maybe with some other friends,

2514
03:09:59,733 --> 03:10:03,066
all around from the north
of India to the south.

2515
03:10:04,500 --> 03:10:06,566
Now allow me to also comment

2516
03:10:06,566 --> 03:10:09,866
about one of the books that
first drew me toward India

2517
03:10:09,866 --> 03:10:12,933
and to its deep history of philosophical

2518
03:10:12,933 --> 03:10:15,066
and spiritual traditions.

2519
03:10:15,066 --> 03:10:18,166
The book is "Siddhartha" by Herman Hesse.

2520
03:10:19,000 --> 03:10:22,400
I first read most of Hesse's
major work as a teenager,

2521
03:10:22,400 --> 03:10:26,000
but then reread them
again through the years.

2522
03:10:26,000 --> 03:10:28,566
It first found me, "Siddhartha,"

2523
03:10:28,566 --> 03:10:32,466
when I was immersed in a very
different kind of literature

2524
03:10:32,466 --> 03:10:35,566
of Dostoevsky, Camus, Kafka, Orwell,

2525
03:10:35,566 --> 03:10:38,766
Hemingway, Kerouac, Steinbeck, and so on.

2526
03:10:38,766 --> 03:10:41,966
Many of these explore
the same human condition

2527
03:10:41,966 --> 03:10:44,466
that puzzled me when I was a young man,

2528
03:10:44,466 --> 03:10:49,033
and still puzzles me today even more so.

2529
03:10:49,033 --> 03:10:51,100
But "Siddhartha" was my introduction

2530
03:10:51,100 --> 03:10:54,600
to the Eastern way of
looking at these puzzles.

2531
03:10:54,600 --> 03:10:57,400
It was written by Herman
Hesse, and by the way,

2532
03:10:57,400 --> 03:10:59,833
please allow me this
pronunciation of his last name.

2533
03:10:59,833 --> 03:11:01,133
I've heard some people say Hesse,

2534
03:11:01,133 --> 03:11:04,666
but my whole life I've always said Hesse.

2535
03:11:04,666 --> 03:11:07,266
So anyway, it was written by Herman Hesse,

2536
03:11:07,266 --> 03:11:10,166
a German Swiss Nobel prize-winning writer

2537
03:11:10,166 --> 03:11:13,166
during one of the darkest
periods of his own life.

2538
03:11:13,166 --> 03:11:14,800
His marriage was failing,

2539
03:11:14,800 --> 03:11:17,766
World War I had shattered
his pacifist ideals

2540
03:11:17,766 --> 03:11:20,466
and he suffered from
debilitating headaches,

2541
03:11:20,466 --> 03:11:22,566
insomnia, and depression.

2542
03:11:22,566 --> 03:11:25,866
During this period, he began
psychoanalysis with Carl Jung,

2543
03:11:25,866 --> 03:11:29,433
which in part led him to
explore Eastern philosophies

2544
03:11:29,433 --> 03:11:31,766
as a way to heal his fractured psyche.

2545
03:11:32,733 --> 03:11:36,166
Hesse immersed himself in
translations of ancient Hindu

2546
03:11:36,166 --> 03:11:39,933
and Buddhist texts,
studying the "Upanishads"

2547
03:11:39,933 --> 03:11:42,233
and the "Bhagavad Gita."

2548
03:11:42,233 --> 03:11:45,900
And so the writing of
"Siddhartha" was in itself,

2549
03:11:45,900 --> 03:11:47,300
for him, a journey

2550
03:11:47,300 --> 03:11:50,633
that paralleled that of the
main character in the book.

2551
03:11:50,633 --> 03:11:54,066
Hesse started writing the book in 1919

2552
03:11:54,066 --> 03:11:57,166
and finished three years
later, experiencing

2553
03:11:57,166 --> 03:12:00,233
an extensive psychological
crisis in the middle.

2554
03:12:01,066 --> 03:12:04,600
The book follows Siddhartha,
a young man in ancient India

2555
03:12:04,600 --> 03:12:07,033
as he leaves behind wealth and comfort

2556
03:12:07,033 --> 03:12:08,800
to search for meaning.

2557
03:12:08,800 --> 03:12:12,066
You can feel his personal
struggle in every page.

2558
03:12:12,066 --> 03:12:15,100
Siddhartha's restlessness,
his dissatisfaction

2559
03:12:15,100 --> 03:12:18,266
with conventional wisdom,
his need to find truth,

2560
03:12:18,266 --> 03:12:20,166
the direct experience.

2561
03:12:20,166 --> 03:12:22,166
Again, the book wasn't simply

2562
03:12:22,166 --> 03:12:24,466
a philosophical exploration for Hesse,

2563
03:12:24,466 --> 03:12:27,533
it was psychological survival.

2564
03:12:27,533 --> 03:12:30,166
He was writing his way out of suffering

2565
03:12:30,166 --> 03:12:33,133
and towards his own enlightenment.

2566
03:12:33,133 --> 03:12:35,466
I won't go into a deep
analysis of the book here,

2567
03:12:35,466 --> 03:12:38,900
but I will mention two
key lessons I took away

2568
03:12:38,900 --> 03:12:41,233
and carried with me to this day.

2569
03:12:41,233 --> 03:12:44,433
First lesson comes from
this scene in the book

2570
03:12:44,433 --> 03:12:48,266
that to me is one of the great
scenes in all of literature.

2571
03:12:48,266 --> 03:12:52,133
Siddhartha is sitting by
a river just listening,

2572
03:12:52,133 --> 03:12:55,866
and in that river he hears
all of life, all sounds,

2573
03:12:55,866 --> 03:13:00,366
all voices, all of time,
past, present, future

2574
03:13:00,366 --> 03:13:01,833
flowing together as one.

2575
03:13:03,000 --> 03:13:06,133
That scene gave me the
experience and the notion

2576
03:13:06,133 --> 03:13:08,466
that while in some grounded human sense,

2577
03:13:08,466 --> 03:13:11,700
the linear arrow of time does exist.

2578
03:13:11,700 --> 03:13:15,500
In another sense, time
is a kind of illusion,

2579
03:13:15,500 --> 03:13:19,600
that in fact, everything
exists simultaneously.

2580
03:13:19,600 --> 03:13:24,000
That our lives are both
momentary and eternal.

2581
03:13:25,033 --> 03:13:28,233
It is hard to describe
these ideas with words,

2582
03:13:28,233 --> 03:13:31,600
I think they must be experienced
as personal revelations.

2583
03:13:32,800 --> 03:13:37,200
I'm reminded of the fish story
that David Foster Wallace,

2584
03:13:37,200 --> 03:13:39,733
another one of my favorite writers,

2585
03:13:39,733 --> 03:13:43,566
described in a commencement
speech 20 years ago.

2586
03:13:43,566 --> 03:13:47,600
The story goes, two young
fish are swimming along

2587
03:13:47,600 --> 03:13:50,933
when they encounter an older
fish swimming the opposite way.

2588
03:13:51,800 --> 03:13:54,033
The older fish nods and says,

2589
03:13:54,033 --> 03:13:56,633
"Morning boys, how's the water?"

2590
03:13:57,666 --> 03:13:59,566
The young fish swim on,

2591
03:13:59,566 --> 03:14:02,533
and eventually one turns
to the other and asks,

2592
03:14:02,533 --> 03:14:03,933
"What the hell is water?"

2593
03:14:04,800 --> 03:14:08,166
The illusion of the
forward progress of time

2594
03:14:08,166 --> 03:14:10,666
is water in this metaphor.

2595
03:14:10,666 --> 03:14:13,500
As humans, we're fully immersed in it,

2596
03:14:13,500 --> 03:14:16,866
but enlightenment in part
involves being able to step back

2597
03:14:16,866 --> 03:14:20,400
and get a glimpse at another
deeper perspective on reality

2598
03:14:20,400 --> 03:14:24,000
where all things are
inextricably interconnected

2599
03:14:24,000 --> 03:14:26,466
across both time and space.

2600
03:14:28,033 --> 03:14:30,233
Another key lesson from the novel

2601
03:14:30,233 --> 03:14:32,900
that was especially formative
to me as a young man

2602
03:14:32,900 --> 03:14:36,266
was that one should not
blindly follow others,

2603
03:14:36,266 --> 03:14:39,200
or learn about the world
exclusively through books.

2604
03:14:39,200 --> 03:14:41,666
But rather forge your own path

2605
03:14:41,666 --> 03:14:43,366
and thrust yourself into the world

2606
03:14:43,366 --> 03:14:46,266
where the lessons of
life can only be learned

2607
03:14:46,266 --> 03:14:48,300
by experiencing them directly.

2608
03:14:49,400 --> 03:14:52,000
And every experience, both
positive and negative,

2609
03:14:52,000 --> 03:14:56,033
mistakes, suffering, and
even seemingly wasted time

2610
03:14:56,033 --> 03:14:59,433
is all an essential part of growth.

2611
03:15:00,566 --> 03:15:02,866
To this point, Hesse draws a distinction

2612
03:15:02,866 --> 03:15:04,933
between knowledge and wisdom.

2613
03:15:04,933 --> 03:15:06,966
Knowledge can be taught by others.

2614
03:15:06,966 --> 03:15:08,900
Wisdom can only be gathered

2615
03:15:08,900 --> 03:15:11,766
through experiencing the
full mess of life yourself.

2616
03:15:12,966 --> 03:15:16,033
In other words, the path to understanding

2617
03:15:16,033 --> 03:15:18,466
isn't through rejection of the world,

2618
03:15:18,466 --> 03:15:20,966
but through complete immersion in it.

2619
03:15:21,800 --> 03:15:24,233
Those are my early steps
in seeing the world

2620
03:15:24,233 --> 03:15:26,933
through the lens of Eastern philosophy.

2621
03:15:26,933 --> 03:15:30,066
But many of Hesse's books
had an impact on me.

2622
03:15:30,066 --> 03:15:35,066
I would recommend to read
"Demian" when you are younger,

2623
03:15:35,233 --> 03:15:38,266
"Steppenwolf" when you are older,

2624
03:15:38,266 --> 03:15:39,933
"Siddhartha" throughout your life,

2625
03:15:39,933 --> 03:15:43,766
especially in moments of crisis,
and "The Glass Bead Game"

2626
03:15:43,766 --> 03:15:46,266
if you want to take on
Hesse's magnum opus,

2627
03:15:46,266 --> 03:15:49,566
that rigorously explores
the ways the human mind

2628
03:15:49,566 --> 03:15:51,266
and human civilization

2629
03:15:51,266 --> 03:15:54,266
can engage in the pursuit of
knowledge, wisdom, and meaning.

2630
03:15:55,600 --> 03:15:56,466
But "Siddhartha"

2631
03:15:56,466 --> 03:15:59,566
is the only one I've
returned to more than twice.

2632
03:15:59,566 --> 03:16:02,766
In my own life, when faced
with a difficult situation,

2633
03:16:02,766 --> 03:16:05,166
I often return to the moment in the book

2634
03:16:05,166 --> 03:16:08,833
when Siddhartha is asked
what skills he possesses,

2635
03:16:08,833 --> 03:16:10,533
and his answer is simply,

2636
03:16:10,533 --> 03:16:14,600
"I can think, I can wait, I can fast."

2637
03:16:15,666 --> 03:16:17,066
Let me elaborate.

2638
03:16:17,066 --> 03:16:20,266
Indeed, for the first part, "I can think,"

2639
03:16:20,266 --> 03:16:23,133
as Marcus Aurelius said,
"The quality of your life

2640
03:16:23,133 --> 03:16:25,633
is determined by the
quality of your thoughts."

2641
03:16:26,466 --> 03:16:29,466
For the second part, "I can wait,"

2642
03:16:29,466 --> 03:16:33,100
patience and waiting often is indeed

2643
03:16:33,100 --> 03:16:35,733
the optimal decision
when facing a problem.

2644
03:16:35,733 --> 03:16:38,566
Time does bring clarity
and depth of understanding.

2645
03:16:39,600 --> 03:16:42,966
For the third part, "I can fast,"

2646
03:16:42,966 --> 03:16:47,733
when needed, being able to
live and flourish with less

2647
03:16:47,733 --> 03:16:50,133
is a prerequisite of being free,

2648
03:16:50,133 --> 03:16:51,966
when the mind, the body, and society

2649
03:16:51,966 --> 03:16:54,666
all are trying to put you in cages.

2650
03:16:56,000 --> 03:16:57,500
All right, friends.

2651
03:16:57,500 --> 03:17:00,333
Now, sadly, our time
together in this episode

2652
03:17:00,333 --> 03:17:02,400
has come to a close.

2653
03:17:02,400 --> 03:17:04,900
As always, thank you for being here

2654
03:17:04,900 --> 03:17:07,700
and thank you for your
support through the years.

2655
03:17:08,600 --> 03:17:12,333
Let me leave you with a few
words from the "Bhagavad Gita."

2656
03:17:13,533 --> 03:17:17,100
"He who experiences the unity of life,

2657
03:17:17,100 --> 03:17:19,933
sees his own self in all beings,

2658
03:17:19,933 --> 03:17:23,766
and all beings in his own self,

2659
03:17:23,766 --> 03:17:26,933
and looks onto everything
with an impartial eye."

2660
03:17:28,100 --> 03:17:31,500
Thank you for listening. I
hope to see you next time.

